000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 67\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 3\n |Title = Five Miles Per Day\n |Aux2 = Katy Wix\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|9|18|df=y}}\n |Viewers = 1,413,000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 68\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 4\n |Title = Quisps\n |Aux2 = Rose Matafeo\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|9|25|df=y}}\n |Viewers = 1,287,000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 69\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 5\n |Title = Another Spoon\n |Aux2 = Jo Brand\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|10|2|df=y}}\n |Viewers = 1,277,000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 70\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 6\n |Title = Bready Bready Bready\n |Aux2 = Ed Gamble\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|10|9|df=y}}\n |Viewers = 1,215,000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 71\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 7\n |Title = A Cuddle\n |Aux2 = Katy Wix\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|10|16|df=y}}\n |Viewers = 1,151,000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 72\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 8\n |Title = Shaqinahat\n |Aux2 = Ed Gamble\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|10|23|df=y}}\n |Viewers = 1,343,000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 73\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 9\n |Title = Don't Like Them Go Bang\n |Aux2 = David Baddiel\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|10|30|df=y}}\n |Viewers = 1,364,000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 74\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 10\n |Title = Think About The Spirit\n |Aux2 = Ed Gamble\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|11|6|df=y}}\n |Viewers = 1,378,000\n}}\n}}\n\n== International broadcasts ==\nThe show is also broadcast in [[Belgium]], [[Denmark]], [[Iceland]], [[Sweden]], [[South Africa]], [[Norway]], [[Finland]], [[Australia]] and [[New Zealand]].\n\n== International versions ==\nInternational versions of the programme have been made in Belgium (as ''Het Grootste Licht'') [The Greatest Light],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vtm.be/het-grootste-licht|title=Het Grootste Licht|publisher=[[VTM (TV channel)|VTM]]|language=Dutch|accessdate=7 December 2017}}</ref> Sweden (as ''[[B\u00e4st i Test]]'') [Best in Test],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.svtplay.se/bast-i-test|title=B\u00e4st i test|publisher=[[Sveriges Television]]|language=Swedish|accessdate=7 December 2017}}</ref> and Norway ''(as Kongen befaler, 'The King commands')''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tvguide.vg.no/program/kongen-befaler|title=Kongen befaler|website=VG TV-guide|language=no|access-date=25 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"US announced\"/> In Denmark the programme is titled ''Stormester'' ('Grandmaster') and premiered on 25 August 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tv.tv2.dk/stormester|title=Stormester|website=tv.tv2.dk|language=da-DK|access-date=27 September 2018}}</ref> In April 2017, a [[Taskmaster (American TV series)|US version]] with [[Reggie Watts]] as the Taskmaster and Horne as the assistant was announced, made by Avalon, the same production company for the UK version and originally aired on [[Comedy Central]] on 27 April 2018.<ref name=\"US announced\">{{cite web|url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/tv/news/2535/taskmaster_usa/|title=Comedy Central USA buys Taskmaster format|publisher=[[British Comedy Guide]]|date=18 April 2017|accessdate=20 April 2017}}</ref> A German version featuring [[Atze Schr\u00f6der]] as the Taskmaster was commissioned by [[RTL (German TV channel)|RTL]] in 2017; two episodes were recorded but not broadcast.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dwdl.de/nachrichten/61654/atze_schrder_bekommt_neue_comedyshow_bei_rtl/|title=Atze Schr\u00f6der bekommt neue Comedyshow bei RTL|last=Pohlig|first=Marcel|date=25 May 2017|website=DWDL.de|language=de|access-date=18 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.quotenmeter.de/n/101333/atze-schroeders-taskmaster-gelangt-nicht-auf-die-schirme|title=Atze Schr\u00f6ders \"Taskmaster\" gelangt nicht auf die Schirme|date=30 May 2018|last=Schering|first=Sidney|website=Quotenmeter|language=de-DE|access-date=18 March 2019}}</ref> In 2019 it was announced a New Zealand version would be produced for broadcast in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/tv-radio/116150568/tvnz-to-produce-local-version-of-taskmaster-mean-mums-and-golden-boy-back-for-second-season|title=TVNZ to produce local version of Taskmaster, Mean Mums and Golden Boy back for second season|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n\n== Book ==\nA tie-in book, ''Taskmaster \u2014 200 Extraordinary Tasks for Ordinary People'', was written by Alex Horne and published by [[Penguin Random House]] on 6 September 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/shop/news/3055/taskmaster_book/|title=Alex Horne pens Taskmaster book|work=[[British Comedy Guide]]|date=24 April 2018|accessdate=28 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nTask 185 in the book provided the latitude and longitude of a Buckinghamshire park, with instructions to meet there at midday on 14 September 2019 for a picnic and Taskmaster tour. The event was attended by around 1800 people with Horne himself present to show attendees filming locations from the show.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chortle.co.uk/news/2019/09/16/44324/the_taskmaster_army|title=The Taskmaster Army|work=[[Chortle]]|date=16 September 2019|accessdate=4 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, a paperback edition was published, with 20 new tasks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Taskmaster-Extraordinary-Tasks-Ordinary-People/dp/1785943588|title=220 Extraordinary Tasks For Ordinary People|work=[[Amazon (company)|Amazon]]|date=5 September 2019|accessdate=18 October 2019}}</ref> As well as writing additional tasks, Horne also removed the expiration date of 31 December 2019 where it appeared, and replaced tasks that had a set date to be achieved on.\n\n== Reception ==\n=== Critical reception ===\nAndrew Billen of ''[[The Times]]'' gave a five star review of the show's first episode, \"Melon Buffet\", calling it \"funny, revealing, and glorious\" and comparing it to ''[[The Generation Game]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/tv-review-taskmaster-brits-behind-bars-k5sxh082s2p|title=TV review: Taskmaster; Brits Behind Bars|work=[[The Times]]|last=Billen|first=Andrew|date=29 July 2015|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref> In another review of the first episode, Filipa Jodelka of ''[[The Guardian]]'' describes ''Taskmaster'' as a panel show with an \"edgy parlour-game twist\". Jodelka praises the \"molten-hot banter\" between contestants and Davies, and compares the arbitrary awarding of points to ''[[QI (TV series)|QI]]'' and ''[[Numberwang]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2015/jul/28/dave-game-show-taskmaster|title=Taskmaster: 'Nato should be informed of its molten-hot banter'|work=[[The Guardian]]|last=Jodelka|first=Filipa|date=28 July 2015|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref> Also reviewing \"Melon Buffet\", Ellen Jones of ''[[The Independent]]'' praised the show as entertaining despite its \"informal and cheap-looking\" style.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/taskmaster-dave-tv-review-as-informal-and-cheap-looking-as-an-evening-at-your-local-pub-10421823.html|title=Taskmaster, Dave - TV review: As informal and cheap-looking as an evening at your local pub|work=[[The Independent]]|last=Jones|first=Ellen E|date=28 July 2015|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nWesley Mead of ''Den of Geek'' wrote a positive review in 2016, praising the show as the \"crowning jewel\" of original programming on [[Dave (TV channel)|Dave]], and approving of the design of the tasks and the range of approaches that contestants demonstrate. Mead believes that the second series was an improvement on the first, but criticises that the first three series have only one female contestant apiece.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denofgeek.com/uk/tv/taskmaster/44706/taskmaster-one-of-tvs-funniest-most-unexpected-comedies|title=Taskmaster: one of TV's funniest, most unexpected comedies|work=Den of Geek|publisher=[[Dennis Publishing]]|last=Mead|first=Wesley|date=25 April 2017|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Awards and nominations ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"  style=\"font-size:95%; width:99%;\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Recipients\n! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" | 2016\n| [[British Comedy Guide#2016|Comedy.co.uk Awards 2016]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/awards/2016/|title=The Comedy.co.uk Awards 2016|publisher=British Comedy Guide|date=23 January 2017|accessdate=29 January 2018}}</ref>\n| Best TV Entertainment Show\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 2017\n|[[2017 British Academy Television Awards|British Academy Television Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bafta.org/television/comedy-comedy-entertainment-programme|title=Comedy & Comedy Entertainment Programme - CHARLIE BROOKER'S 2016 WIPE|publisher=[[British Academy Film Awards]]|access-date=7 December 2017|url-status=live|archive-date=15 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170415133707/http://www.bafta.org/television/comedy-comedy-entertainment-programme}}</ref>\n| Best Comedy and Comedy Entertainment Programme\n| Alex Horne, Andy Cartwright, Andy Devonshire\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[45th International Emmy Awards|International Emmy Award]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iemmys.tv/awards_nominees.aspx|title=2017 International Emmy\u00ae Awards Nominees|access-date=7 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171126035807/https://www.iemmys.tv/awards_nominees.aspx|archive-date=26 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| Non-Scripted Entertainment\n| Avalon Television, Dave\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Royal Television Society|RTS Programme Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rts.org.uk/award/rts-programme-awards-2017|title=RTS Programme Awards 2017|publisher=[[Royal Television Society]]|access-date=7 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170416125906/https://rts.org.uk/award/rts-programme-awards-2017|archive-date=16 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| Best Entertainment Programme\n| Avalon Television\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[British Comedy Guide#2017|Comedy.co.uk Awards 2017]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/awards/2017/|title=The Comedy.co.uk Awards 2017|publisher=British Comedy Guide|date=29 January 2018|accessdate=29 January 2018}}</ref>\n| Best TV Entertainment Show\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{win}}\n|-\n|2018\n|[[2018 British Academy Television Awards|British Academy Television Awards]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bafta.org/media-centre/press-releases/nominations-announced-for-tv-awards-2018|title=Nominations Announced for the Virgin TV British Academy Television Awards in 2018|website=www.bafta.org|language=en|access-date=3 July 2018}}</ref>\n|Best Comedy and Comedy Entertainment Programme\n|Alex Horne, Andy Cartwright, Andy Devonshire\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|https://www.taskmaster.tv/}}\n* {{British Comedy Guide|tv|taskmaster}}\n* {{UKGameshow|Taskmaster}}\n* {{IMDb title}}\n\n{{Dave original programming}}\n\n[[Category:2010s British game shows]]\n[[Category:2020s British game shows]]\n[[Category:2015 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Dave (TV channel) television programmes]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:British panel games]]\n[[Category:2010s British comedy television series]]\n[[Category:2020s British comedy television series]]\n[[Category:Television game shows with incorrect disambiguation]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|British comedy panel game show}}\n{{About||the comic book character|Taskmaster (comics){{!}}Taskmaster|other uses|Taskmaster (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Taskmaster\n| image                    = Taskmaster logo.jpg\n| caption                  = \n| show_name_2              = \n| genre                    = {{Plainlist}}\n* [[Comedy]]\n* [[Panel game]]\n{{Endplainlist}}\n| creator                  = [[Alex Horne]]\n| developer                = \n| writer                   = \n| director                 = {{Plainlist}}\n* Andy Devonshire\n* Peter Orton\n{{Endplainlist}}\n| creative_director        = \n| presenter                = {{Plainlist}}\n* [[Greg Davies]]\n* [[Alex Horne]]\n{{Endplainlist}}\n| starring                 = \n| judges                   = \n| voices                   = \n| narrated                 = \n| theme_music_composer     = [[The Horne Section]]\n| opentheme                = \n| endtheme                 = \n| composer                 = {{Plainlist}}\n* [[Dru Masters]]\n* Tom Howe\n{{Endplainlist}}\n| country                  = United Kingdom\n| language                 = English\n| num_episodes             = 74 <small>(inc. 2 specials)</small>\n| list_episodes            = #Episodes\n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist}}\n* Richard Allen-Turner\n* James Taylor\n* Jon Thoday\n* Hilary Rosen\n* Rob Aslett\n* Richard Watsham\n* Andy Devonshire\n* Alex Horne\n{{Endplainlist}}\n| producer                 = {{Plainlist}}\n* Andy Cartwright\n* Alex Horne\n{{Endplainlist}}\n| location                 = \n| cinematography           = \n| editor                   = {{Plainlist}}\n* Thomas Perrett\n* Mark Sangster\n{{Endplainlist}}\n| camera                   = \n| runtime                  = 60 minutes <small>(inc. adverts)</small>\n| company                  = Avalon Television\n| distributor              = \n| picture_format           = [[16:9]] ([[1080i]] [[HDTV]])\n| audio_format             = \n| first_run                = \n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2015|7|28|df=y}}\n| last_aired               = present\n| preceded_by              = \n| followed_by              = \n| related                  = [[B&auml;st i Test|''B&auml;st i Test'' (Swedish TV Series)]]\n[[Taskmaster (American TV series)|''Taskmaster'' (US TV series)]]\n[[Kongen Befaler (Norwegian TV series)|''Kongen Befaler'' (Norwegian TV series)]]\n| website                  = http://taskmaster.tv\n| website_title            = Official website\n| production_website       = \n| num_series               = 9 (+ 2 specials)\n| channel                  = [[Dave (TV channel)|Dave]] <small>(2015\u20132019)</small><br/>[[Channel 4]] <small>(2020\u2013present)\n}}\n\n'''''Taskmaster''''' is a British comedy [[panel game]] show originally created by British comedian [[Alex Horne]] during the [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]] in 2010, and adapted for television in 2015. New episodes premiered on [[Dave (TV channel)|Dave]] from 2015 until 2019, when the series was acquired by [[Channel 4]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Warner |first1=Sam |title=Taskmaster is officially moving to Channel 4 |url=https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/a29888005/taskmaster-moving-channel-4/ |accessdate=22 November 2019 |work=Digital Spy |publisher=HEARST UK ENTERTAINMENT NETWORK |date=22 November 2019}}</ref> The TV series stars comedian and actor [[Greg Davies]] in the title role of the Taskmaster, issuing simple comedic and bizarre tasks to five regular contestants \u2013 usually comedians \u2013 with  Alex Horne acting as Davies's assistant and as umpire during the challenges.\n\n{{Aired episodes|2019|11|6|num=74|title=Taskmaster|finished=9|specials=2|uk=y}} Channel 4 has commissioned six additional series, which will air over three years from late 2020.<ref>{{cite news |title=Taskmaster snapped up by Channel 4 {{!}} Channel 4 |url=https://www.channel4.com/press/news/taskmaster-snapped-channel-4 |accessdate=22 November 2019 |publisher=Channel Four Television Corporation |date=22 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nInternational versions of the programme have been made in Belgium (as {{lang|nl|Het Grootste Licht}}, 'The Greatest Light'), Sweden (as ''[[B\u00e4st i Test]]'', 'Best in test'), Spain (as {{lang|es|Dicho y hecho}}, 'Said and done'), Denmark (as {{lang|da|Stormester}}, 'Grandmaster'), and Norway (as {{lang|no|Kongen befaler}}, literally 'The King commands', the Norwegian name of the game 'Simon Says'), and a [[Taskmaster (U.S. TV series)|US version]] with [[Reggie Watts]] and Horne began in April 2018.\n\n==Format==\nThe game consists of simple and bizarre challenges, ostensibly set to the contestants by Davies in his role as the Taskmaster, with assistance provided by Horne. The tasks \u2013 usually performed in isolation, but occasionally in teams \u2013 are designed to encourage the players to [[Lateral thinking|think laterally]] and creatively to complete the task.\n\nEach episode starts with the Prize Task, where each contestant donates a prize to offer up following a given theme \u2013 e.g. the contestant's most unusual item; their most treasured item; their trendiest item of clothing etc \u2013 and are all awarded to the winner of the particular episode.\n\nThree or four pre-filmed tasks follow, usually taking place in and around the Taskmaster house. Tasks are delivered to the players in an envelope with a [[Seal (emblem)|wax seal]], which the player reads aloud: e.g. \"Completely empty this [[bathtub]] \u2013 fastest wins\" or \"Impress this mayor \u2013 you have 20 minutes\". After the tasks are shown to the audience, the players justify their creative methods and argue to Davies \u2013 and among themselves \u2013 as to why they did best. After all the attempts at the task have been seen, judgement is passed by Davies and points are awarded (or players disqualified) accordingly. Normally the winner of the task gets five points, with second place score four points and so on. Some episodes feature team tasks, in which one group of two contestants and a second group of three contestants work together. The groups remain the same throughout each series. Generally, five points are split between the teams, with each member getting the same number.\n\nThe final challenge is performed live in the studio. In the event of a [[Tie (draw)|tie]], the winner is decided by a special tie-breaker task, which may either be pre-filmed or performed live.\n\nIn addition to the prizes for each episode, at the end of each series a trophy is presented to the contestant who has scored the most points over the course of the entire series. From the second series onward, the trophy took the form of a golden [[Bust (sculpture)|bust]] of Davies.\n\n== History ==\n=== Conception and beginning ===\nAccording to creator [[Alex Horne]], the show was inspired by ''[[The Crystal Maze]]'', his time working on ''[[Big Brother (UK TV series)|Big Brother]]'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/big-brother/interviews/a659463/alex-horne-taskmaster-was-inspired-by-the-crystal-maze-and-big-brother/|title=Alex Horne: Big Brother inspired Taskmaster|date=21 July 2015|work=Digital Spy|access-date=26 September 2017|language=en}}</ref> and his jealousy at his friend Tim Key's win of the [[Edinburgh Comedy Awards|Edinburgh Comedy Award]].<ref name=\"i interview\"/>\n\nHorne first tested the idea in 2009, where he set 20 comedians \u2013 including [[Stuart Goldsmith]], [[Josie Long]], [[Mark Watson]], [[Tim Key]], [[Joe Wilkinson]] and eventual winner [[Mike Wozniak]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/fringe/2010/alex_horne_the_taskmaster/20160711|title=Alex Horne: The Taskmaster - Edinburgh Fringe 2010 - British Comedy Guide|last=Guide|first=British Comedy|website=British Comedy Guide|language=en-GB|access-date=26 September 2017}}</ref> \u2013 monthly tasks by email over the course of a year. The first task was \"Put as much money into my bank account \u2013 most money wins.\"<ref name=\"i interview\"/><ref name=\"chortle commission\"/> At the 2010 [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]], he hosted \"The Taskmaster\",<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://tv.bt.com/tv/tv-from-bt/5-things-to-know-about-daves-original-comedy-show-taskmaster-11364175361015|title=5 things to know about Dave\u2019s original comedy show Taskmaster|work=BT.com|access-date=26 September 2017|language=en}}</ref> a \"two-hour drunken show\"<ref name=\"i interview\">{{cite web|url=https://inews.co.uk/essentials/culture/television/taskmaster-alex-horne-interview-dave/|title=Taskmaster: how Alex Horne's Fringe show became a transatlantic comedy hit|work=[[i (newspaper)|i]]|last=Nelson|first=Alex|date=11 September 2017|accessdate=13 September 2017}}</ref> where he revealed the players' attempts at each task and announced the winner. Horne hosted \"Taskmaster II\" the following year with ten contestants;<ref name=\"chortle commission\"/> it was won by Josie Long.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/edinburgh-theatre/reviews/08-2011/alex-horne-taskmaster-ii_7224.html|title=Alex Horne: Taskmaster II|work=WhatsOnStage.com|access-date=26 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nWith Avalon as the production company, Horne pitched the programme to several different broadcasters, including [[Channel 4]], before it was picked up by [[Dave (channel)|Dave]]. Hilary Rosen was Deputy Director of Commissioning for the channel at the time; she was concerned with the structure of the show, as the same contestants feature in every episode of a series. This differs from other [[panel show]]s, though Horne describes ''Taskmaster'' as \"more like a [[sitcom]]\". Another issue with this format point is that it made shooting a traditional [[television pilot|pilot]] implausible.<ref name=\"chortle commission\"/> However, the aspects of the show filmed before a studio audience were tested in a pilot.<ref name=\"comedy 10\"/> In the first series, the show was shot with the intention that the episodes could be shown in any order, though Rosen later realised that \"this was a show you record and transmit in the same order\", comparing the show to a [[soap opera]].<ref name=\"chortle commission\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chortle.co.uk/news/2017/11/09/38372/why_taskmaster_was_a_hard_sell...|title=Why Taskmaster was a hard sell...|work=[[Chortle]]|date=9 November 2017|accessdate=7 December 2017}}</ref> Horne says that the comedians began to sign up for the show after [[Frank Skinner]] agreed to take part.<ref name=\"chortle commission\"/>\n\n=== Broadcast ===\nThe first series was announced on 19 September 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/tv/news/1610/taskmaster_starring_alex_horne_and_greg_davies/|title=Alex Horne and Greg Davies star in new show Taskmaster|publisher=[[British Comedy Guide]]|date=19 September 2014|accessdate=7 December 2017}}</ref> Lasting six episodes, it aired in 2015 from 28 July to 1 September, featuring contestants [[Frank Skinner]], [[Josh Widdicombe]], [[Roisin Conaty]], [[Romesh Ranganathan]] and [[Tim Key]]. The winner of the series was Josh Widdicombe.\n\nOn 24 September 2015, it was announced that the show had been recommissioned for a second and third series,<ref>{{cite web|date=24 September 2015|url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/tv/news/1897/taskmaster_return_dave_series_2_and_3/|title=Taskmaster to return for two new series|publisher=[[British Comedy Guide]]|accessdate=24 September 2015}}</ref> and the second series premiered on 21 June 2016. Lasting five episodes and concluding on 19 July, the series featured [[Doc Brown (rapper)|Doc Brown]], [[Joe Wilkinson]], [[Jon Richardson]], [[Katherine Ryan]] and [[Richard Osman]], with Katherine Ryan becoming the eventual winner.\n\nA one-off special edition featuring five television executives was presented as a stage show during the 2016 [[Edinburgh International Television Festival]]. This version included pre-recorded tasks filmed at the house location and a final stage task.<ref>{{cite AV media | title = Edinburgh Does... Taskmaster | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IKmKharkSzc | access-date =3 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe third series, also consisting of five episodes, was initially planned for 2017 but aired earlier due to positive reception of the previous series;<ref name=\"recommissioned\"/> it was broadcast from 4 October 2016 to 1 November. The contestants for series three were [[Al Murray]], [[Dave Gorman]], [[Paul Chowdhry]], [[Rob Beckett]] and [[Sara Pascoe]]; the winner was Rob Beckett.\n\nOn 3 October 2016, the show was renewed for a fourth and fifth series, each of which were to last eight episodes.<ref name=\"recommissioned\">{{cite web|date=3 October 2016|url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/tv/news/2246/taskmaster_series_4_and_5/|title=Dave orders Taskmaster Series 4 and Series 5|publisher=[[British Comedy Guide]]|accessdate=3 October 2016}}</ref> Series four featured [[Hugh Dennis]], [[Joe Lycett]], [[Lolly Adefope]], [[Mel Giedroyc]] and [[Noel Fielding]], and culminated in a win for Noel Fielding. It was broadcast in 2017 from 25 April to 13 June. The fifth series aired in the same year from 6 September to 1 November, with a line-up of [[Aisling Bea]], [[Bob Mortimer]], [[Mark Watson]], [[Nish Kumar]] and [[Sally Phillips]]. The winner was Bob Mortimer.\n\nA two part \"Champion of Champions\" special was announced in September 2017; the first part aired on 13 December 2017 with the second part on 20 December.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denofgeek.com/uk/tv/taskmaster/50119/taskmaster-2-part-champion-of-champions-special-on-its-way|title=Taskmaster: Christmas special air date confirmed|last=Mellor|first=Louisa|work=[[Den of Geek!]]|date=21 November 2017|accessdate=7 December 2017}}</ref> The contestants are the winners of the first five series \u2013 that is, Josh Widdicombe, Katherine Ryan, Rob Beckett, Noel Fielding and Bob Mortimer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chortle.co.uk/news/2017/09/13/37889/taskmaster_to_return_for_a_champion_of_champions_special|title=Taskmaster to return for a 'champion of champions' special|work=Chortle|date=13 September 2017}}</ref> The winner was Josh Widdicombe, who received a life-size trophy of Davies's headless body.\n\nOn 22 February 2018, it was announced that ''Taskmaster'' had been renewed for four more series lasting 10 episodes each. The sixth series, which aired from 2 May to 4 July 2018, featured [[Tim Vine]], [[Russell Howard]], [[Asim Chaudhry]], [[Liza Tarbuck]] and [[Alice Levine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/tv/news/2962/lots_more_taskmaster/|title=Taskmaster gets 40 more episodes|publisher=[[British Comedy Guide]]|date=22 February 2018|accessdate=22 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chortle.co.uk/news/2018/02/21/39194/taskmaster_to_return_for_a_sixth_series|title=Taskmaster gets FOUR new series|publisher=[[British Comedy Guide]]|date=21 February 2018|accessdate=22 February 2018}}</ref> Liza Tarbuck was the winner.\n\nThe seventh series aired between 5 September to 7 November 2018, featured [[James Acaster]], [[Jessica Knappett]], [[Kerry Godliman]], [[Phil Wang]] and [[Rhod Gilbert]].<ref name=\"s7 dog\">{{cite web|url=http://www.denofgeek.com/uk/tv/taskmaster/58895/taskmaster-series-7-line-up-start-date-announced|title=Taskmaster series 7 line-up, start date announced|work=Den of Geek|last=Howard|first=Kirsten|date=14 August 2018|accessdate=15 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/tv/news/3165/taskmaster_series_7_players/|title=Taskmaster Series 7 line-up revealed|publisher=[[British Comedy Guide]]|date=4 July 2018|accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2018-07-04/taskmaster-series-7-full-line-up-confirmed-comedians/|title=Taskmaster unveils new cast of comedians starring in the next series|work=[[Radio Times]]|last=Taylor|first=Frances|date=4 July 2018|accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref> The series was won by Kerry Godliman.\n\nThe contestants for series eight were confirmed by [[Digital Spy]] in February 2019 as<ref>[https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/a26375679/taskmaster-uk-series-8-line-up-the-inbetweeners-love-island-the-chase-celebrities/ Digital Spy, 2019-02-18]</ref> [[Iain Stirling]], [[Joe Thomas (actor)|Joe Thomas]], [[Lou Sanders]], [[Paul Sinha]] and [[Sian Gibson]]. The winner was Lou Sanders.\n\nAfter the conclusion of series eight, the ninth series was confirmed to have contestants [[David Baddiel]], [[Ed Gamble]], [[Jo Brand]], [[Katy Wix]] and [[Rose Matafeo]]. It premiered on 4 September 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/a28684231/taskmaster-series-9-air-date-dave-september-4/|title=Taskmaster series 9 confirms return date \u2013 and it's soon|work=[[Digital Spy]]|last=Houghton|first=Rianne|date=13 August 2019|accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref> The winner was Ed Gamble.\n\nOn 22 November 2019, after talks of the show being bought by another network, it was confirmed that the show would move to [[Channel 4]], and was renewed for six series over the following 3 years to begin in late 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.channel4.com/press/news/taskmaster-snapped-channel-4|title=Taskmaster snapped up by Channel 4|work=[[Channel 4]]|accessdate=22 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Production ==\nTasks are filmed with each contestant separately in a house in [[Chiswick]], London.<ref name=\"dog interview\"/> However, Alex Horne's initial plan was to carry out the tasks in the comedians' houses, saying in an interview: \"I didn't realise how impractical that would be both in terms of cost \u2013 and their lives.\"<ref name=\"chortle commission\"/> Filming tasks takes roughly one day per contestant per episode, filming around eight tasks a day, with each day of filming spread out across several months. Prior to the studio filming, contestants are forbidden to discuss their tasks and are not shown any footage from the tasks, so that studio reactions are genuine.<ref name=\"dog interview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.denofgeek.com/uk/tv/taskmaster/51891/taskmaster-alex-horne-on-series-5-casting-remakes-the-future|title=Taskmaster: Alex Horne on series 5, casting, remakes, the future|work=Den of Geek!|last=Mellor|first=Louisa|date=13 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nHorne designs the tasks to avoid the need for any specialist equipment, so that \"people at home [are] able to do the same things\".<ref name=\"dog interview\"/> Initially, they planned to have Horne show the right way to complete the task after showing the contestants' attempts, but this was abandoned as \"it supposed there was a right way.\"<ref name=\"comedy 10\"/> He also notes that some tasks in the first series involved the general public, but later series avoided this in order to prevent coming across as a \"prank show\". Some tasks are vetoed by producers for pragmatic reasons, such as \"paint the biggest thing red\".<ref name=\"dog interview\"/> Others do not turn out as expected, such as \"burst all these bubbles [on a massive roll of bubble wrap] \u2013 fastest wins\", which had been attempted in three different series but not shown in any of them, as \"it always ends with people jumping on it for hours\".<ref name=\"i interview\"/>\n\nWhen asked why he did not present the show, Horne has said that \"that was never the plan [...] My role as sidekick is to be sneaky and you can run it from the sides in a really funny way.\"<ref name=\"chortle commission\"/> Horne and Greg Davies had never worked together prior to ''Taskmaster'';<ref name=\"comedy 10\">{{cite web|url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/tv/taskmaster/special/10_facts_about_taskmaster/|title=10 things you probably didn't know about Taskmaster|last=Beadle|first=Craig|publisher=[[British Comedy Guide]]|date=10 December 2017|accessdate=11 December 2017}}</ref> Davies was chosen \"because of his authority,\" Horne says in an interview. He adds that in the pilot, Davies acted as a \"dictator figure cross with everyone,\" but his tone in the show is more relaxed, as \"if someone doesn't do something well we really enjoy it so he can be himself.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/tv/taskmaster/interview/alex_horne/|title= Alex Horne interview|publisher=[[British Comedy Guide]]|date=24 April 2017|accessdate=11 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe series director for ''Taskmaster'' is Andy Devonshire, who was previously series director on ''[[The Apprentice (UK TV series)|The Apprentice]]'' and the BBC versions of ''[[The Great British Bake Off]].'' Peter Orton directed the studio for series 2 and 3.  {{Citation needed|reason= It appears Peter Orton died in 2007, please delete or cite accordingly|date=December 2019}} Production designer James Dillion is responsible for the studio and filming locations as well as the caravan featured from series four onwards,<ref name=\"recommissioned\"/> having been past known for designing the original set for ''[[The Crystal Maze]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tv.bt.com/tv/tv-from-bt/5-things-to-know-about-daves-original-comedy-show-taskmaster-11364175361015|title=5 things to know about Dave\u2019s original comedy show Taskmaster|publisher=[[BT Group]]|date=25 April 2017|accessdate=7 December 2017}}</ref> The show's theme music was written and performed by The Horne Section, a jazz band led by Horne.<ref>{{cite web|date=3 December 2016|url=http://greatcentral.org.uk/interview-alex-horne/|title=Interview: Alex Horne|publisher=Great Central|accessdate=20 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Contestants ===\nEach series features five new contestants; the Champion of Champions specials featured the return of the first five series winners. The guests always sit in alphabetical order by first name.<ref name=\"dog interview\"/> Contestants are ordered by first name, with winners highlighted in bold.\n \t\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-3}}\n; Series 1\n*[[Frank Skinner]]\n*'''[[Josh Widdicombe]]'''\n*[[Roisin Conaty]]\n*[[Romesh Ranganathan]]\n*[[Tim Key]]\n{{Col-3}}\n; Series 2\n*[[Doc Brown (rapper)|Doc Brown]]\n*[[Joe Wilkinson]]\n*[[Jon Richardson]]\n*'''[[Katherine Ryan]]'''\n*[[Richard Osman]]\n{{Col-3}}\n; Series 3\n*[[Al Murray]]\n*[[Dave Gorman]]\n*[[Paul Chowdhry]]\n*'''[[Rob Beckett]]'''\n*[[Sara Pascoe]]\n{{Col-end}}\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-3}}\n; Series 4\n*[[Hugh Dennis]]\n*[[Joe Lycett]]\n*[[Lolly Adefope]]\n*[[Mel Giedroyc]]\n*'''[[Noel Fielding]]'''\n{{Col-3}}\n; Series 5\n*[[Aisling Bea]]\n*'''[[Bob Mortimer]]'''\n*[[Mark Watson]]\n*[[Nish Kumar]]\n*[[Sally Phillips]]\n{{Col-3}}\n; Champion of Champions\n*Bob Mortimer\n*'''Josh Widdicombe'''\n*Katherine Ryan\n*Noel Fielding\n*Rob Beckett\n{{Col-end}}\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-3}}\n; Series 6\n*[[Alice Levine]]\n*[[Asim Chaudhry]]\n*'''[[Liza Tarbuck]]'''\n*[[Russell Howard]]\n*[[Tim Vine]]\n{{col-3}}\n; Series 7\n*[[James Acaster]]\n*[[Jessica Knappett]]\n*'''[[Kerry Godliman]]'''\n*[[Phil Wang]]\n*[[Rhod Gilbert]]\n{{col-3}}\n; Series 8\n*[[Iain Stirling]]\n*[[Joe Thomas (actor)|Joe Thomas]]\n*'''[[Lou Sanders]]'''\n*[[Paul Sinha]]\n*[[Sian Gibson]]\n{{col-end}}\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-3}}\n; Series 9\n*[[David Baddiel]]\n*'''[[Ed Gamble]]'''\n*[[Jo Brand]]\n*[[Katy Wix]]\n*[[Rose Matafeo]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Episodes==\n<onlyinclude>{{Series overview\n| seasonT      = Series\n\n| color1       = #FF9999\n| link1        = <includeonly>List of Taskmaster episodes</includeonly>#Series 1 (2015)\n| episodes1    = 6\n| start1       = {{Start date|2015|7|28|df=y}}\n| end1         = {{End date|2015|9|1|df=y}}\n\n| color2       = #FFB399\n| link2        = <includeonly>List of Taskmaster episodes</includeonly>#Series 2 (2016)\n| episodes2    = 5\n| start2       = {{Start date|2016|6|21|df=y}}\n| end2         = {{End date|2016|7|19|df=y}}\n\n| color3       = #FFCC99\n| link3        = <includeonly>List of Taskmaster episodes</includeonly>#Series 3 (2016)\n| episodes3    = 5\n| start3       = {{Start date|2016|10|4|df=y}}\n| end3         = {{End date|2016|11|1|df=y}}\n\n| color4       = #FFE599\n| link4        = <includeonly>List of Taskmaster episodes</includeonly>#Series 4 (2017)\n| episodes4    = 8\n| start4       = {{Start date|2017|4|25|df=y}}\n| end4         = {{End date|2017|6|13|df=y}}\n\n| color5       = #FFFF99\n| link5        = <includeonly>List of Taskmaster episodes</includeonly>#Series 5 (2017)\n| episodes5    = 8\n| start5       