ww.bafta.org/media-centre/press-releases/nominations-announced-for-tv-awards-2018|title=Nominations Announced for the Virgin TV British Academy Television Awards in 2018|website=www.bafta.org|language=en|access-date=3 July 2018}}</ref>\n|Best Comedy and Comedy Entertainment Programme\n|Alex Horne, Andy Cartwright, Andy Devonshire\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|https://www.taskmaster.tv/}}\n* {{British Comedy Guide|tv|taskmaster}}\n* {{UKGameshow|Taskmaster}}\n* {{IMDb title}}\n\n{{Dave original programming}}\n\n[[Category:2010s British game shows]]\n[[Category:2020s British game shows]]\n[[Category:2015 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Dave (TV channel) television programmes]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:British panel games]]\n[[Category:2010s British comedy television series]]\n[[Category:2020s British comedy television series]]\n[[Category:Television game shows with incorrect disambiguation]]\n", "name_user": "212.56.109.209", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(One of your spellings were wrong)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taskmaster_(TV_series)"}
{"title_page": "Kim Pyong-sik", "text_new": "'''Kim Pyong-sik (Hangeul: \uae40\ubcd1\uc2dd, Hanja: \u91d1\u70b3 \u690d)''' (February 10, 1919 - July 21, 1999) was a North Korean politician who served as [[Vice President of North Korea]]\n\n==History==\nHe was born in [[South Jeolla Province]]. Kim Pyong-sik worked for the Union of Korean Students in Japan and the North Korean Central News Agency. After the creation of the General Association of [[Koreans in Japan|Koreans residing in Japan]] ([[Chongryon]], pro-communist organization) in 1955, he held important positions within this organization. Later, he returned to North Korea and joined the [[Korean Social Democratic Party]], a party that became pro-communist under [[Choi Yong-kun]] which closely related with the Workers' Party of Korea. Kim Pyong-sik was a member of the Presidium of the Central Committee of the Korean Social Democratic Party and later became its president. After his resignation as president, he continued to work as an adviser to the Central Committee of the Social Democratic Party and had influence over the party. From 1994 until 1998, he was vice-president of North Korea.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www1.korea-np.co.jp/sinboj/j-2004/01/0401j0205-00002.htm| title = \u7dcf\u9023\u7b2c20\u56de\u5168\u4f53\u5927\u4f1a\u306b\u5411\u3051\u77e5\u308d\u3046\u7dcf\u9023\u306e\u6b69\u307f\uff0811\uff09| publisher = [[\u671d\u9bae\u65b0\u5831]]| date = 2004-02-05| accessdate = 2015-04-01}}</ref> \n\nKim Pyong-sik was also vice chairman of the Standing Committee of the Supreme People's Assembly, North Korea's unicameral parliament.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.sukuukai.jp/mailnews/item_1308.html| title = \u91d1\u65e5\u6210\u304c\u97d3\u56fd\u4eba\u62c9\u81f4\u3001\u91d1\u6b63\u65e5\u306f\u5916\u56fd\u4eba\u3082\u62c9\u81f4\u3092\u6307\u4ee4\uff0d\u62c9\u81f4\u306e\u5168\u8c8c| publisher = [[\u5317\u671d\u9bae\u306b\u62c9\u81f4\u3055\u308c\u305f\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u3092\u6551\u51fa\u3059\u308b\u305f\u3081\u306e\u5168\u56fd\u5354\u8b70\u4f1a]]| date = 2006-08-08| accessdate = 2015-04-01}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Korean Social Democratic Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Supreme People's Assembly]]\n[[Category:Vice Presidents of North Korea]]\n\n[[fr:Kim Pyong-sik]]\n", "text_old": "'''Kim Pyong-sik (Hangeul: \uae40\ubcd1\uc2dd, Hanja: \u91d1\u70b3 \u690d)''' (February 10, 1919 - July 21, 1999) was a North Korean politician who served as [[Vice President of North Korea]]\n\n==History==\nHe was born in [[South Jeolla Province]]. Kim Pyong-sik worked for the Union of Korean Students in Japan and the North Korean Central News Agency. After the creation of the General Association of [[Koreans in Japan|Koreans residing in Japan]] ([[Chongryon]], pro-communist organization) in 1955, he held important positions within this organization. Later, he returned to North Korea and joined the [[Korean Social Democratic Party]], a party that became pro-communist under [[Choi Yong-kun]] which closely related with the Workers' Party of Korea. Kim Pyong-sik was a member of the Presidium of the Central Committee of the Korean Social Democratic Party and later became its president. After his resignation as president, he continued to work as an adviser to the Central Committee of the Social Democratic Party and had influence over the party. From 1994 until 1998, he was vice-president of North Korea.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www1.korea-np.co.jp/sinboj/j-2004/01/0401j0205-00002.htm| title = \u7dcf\u9023\u7b2c20\u56de\u5168\u4f53\u5927\u4f1a\u306b\u5411\u3051\u77e5\u308d\u3046\u7dcf\u9023\u306e\u6b69\u307f\uff0811\uff09| publisher = [[\u671d\u9bae\u65b0\u5831]]| date = 2004-02-05| accessdate = 2015-04-01}}</ref> \n\nKim Pyong-sik was also vice chairman of the Standing Committee of the Supreme People's Assembly, North Korea's unicameral parliament.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.sukuukai.jp/mailnews/item_1308.html| title = \u91d1\u65e5\u6210\u304c\u97d3\u56fd\u4eba\u62c9\u81f4\u3001\u91d1\u6b63\u65e5\u306f\u5916\u56fd\u4eba\u3082\u62c9\u81f4\u3092\u6307\u4ee4\uff0d\u62c9\u81f4\u306e\u5168\u8c8c| publisher = [[\u5317\u671d\u9bae\u306b\u62c9\u81f4\u3055\u308c\u305f\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u3092\u6551\u51fa\u3059\u308b\u305f\u3081\u306e\u5168\u56fd\u5354\u8b70\u4f1a]]| date = 2006-08-08| accessdate = 2015-04-01}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Korean Social Democratic Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Supreme People's Assembly]]\n\n[[fr:Kim Pyong-sik]]\n", "name_user": "Rakoon", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kim_Pyong-sik"}
{"title_page": "Structure of Earth", "text_new": "{{Short description|Inner structure of planet Earth, consisting of several concentric spherical layers}}\n\n[[File:Earth poster.svg|thumb|upright=1.4|Structure of Earth]]\n\nThe internal '''structure of Earth''' is layered in spherical shells: an outer [[silicate mineral|silicate]] solid [[crust (geology)|crust]], a highly [[viscosity|viscous]] [[asthenosphere]] and [[Mantle (geology)|mantle]], a liquid [[Earth's outer core|outer core]] that is much less viscous than the mantle, and a solid [[Earth's inner core|inner core]]. Scientific understanding of the internal structure of [[Earth]] is based on observations of [[topography]] and [[bathymetry]], observations of [[rock (geology)|rock]] in [[outcrop]], samples brought to the surface from greater depths by [[volcano|volcanoes]] or volcanic activity, analysis of the [[seismic wave|seismic waves]] that pass through Earth, measurements of the [[Gravity of Earth|gravitational]] and [[Earth's magnetic field|magnetic fields]] of Earth, and experiments with crystalline solids at pressures and temperatures characteristic of Earth's deep interior.\n\n==Mass==\nThe force exerted by [[Earth's gravity]] can be used to calculate its [[mass]]. Astronomers can also calculate [[Earth mass|Earth's mass]] by observing the motion of orbiting [[satellite|satellites]]. Earth's average [[density]] can be determined through gravimetric experiments, which have historically involved [[pendulum|pendulums]].\n\nThe mass of Earth is about {{val|6|e=24|u=kg}}.<ref name=\"AA\">''M''<sub>E</sub> = 5\u00b79722\u00d710<sup>24</sup> kg \u00b1 6\u00d710<sup>20</sup> kg. \"[http://asa.usno.navy.mil/static/files/2016/Astronomical_Constants_2016.pdf 2016 Selected Astronomical Constants]\" in {{citation|title=The Astronomical Almanac Online|url=http://asa.usno.navy.mil/|publisher=[[United States Naval Observatory|USNO]]\u2013[[United Kingdom Hydrographic Office|UKHO]]}}</ref>\n\n==Structure==\n{{multiple image\n | align     = outer most\n| direction = vertical\n | width     = 300\n<!-- Image 1 -->\n | image1    = RadialDensityPREM.jpg\n | alt1      =\n | caption1  = Earth's radial density distribution according to the preliminary reference earth model (PREM).<ref name=\"prem\">{{cite journal|author=A.M. Dziewonski, D.L. Anderson|title=Preliminary reference Earth model |journal=Physics of the Earth and Planetary Interiors|year= 1981|volume=25|issue=4|pages=297\u2013356|url=https://www.cfa.harvard.edu/~lzeng/papers/PREM.pdf|doi=10.1016/0031-9201(81)90046-7|issn=0031-9201|bibcode=1981PEPI...25..297D}}</ref>\n<!-- Image 2 -->\n | image2    = EarthGravityPREM.svg\n | alt2      =\n | caption2  = Earth's gravity according to the preliminary reference earth model (PREM).<ref name=\"prem\"/>  Comparison to approximations using constant and linear density for Earth's interior.\n<!-- Image 3 -->\n | image3    = Earthquake wave paths.svg\n | alt3      =\n | caption3  = Mapping the interior of [[Earth]] with [[earthquake]] waves.\n<!-- Image 4 -->\n | image4    = Slice earth.svg\n | alt4      =\n | caption4  = Schematic view of the interior of Earth. 1. continental crust \u2013 2. oceanic crust \u2013 3. upper mantle \u2013 4. lower mantle \u2013 5. outer core \u2013 6. inner core \u2013 A: [[Mohorovi\u010di\u0107 discontinuity]] \u2013 B: [[Gutenberg Discontinuity]] \u2013 C: [[Earth's inner core|Lehmann\u2013Bullen discontinuity]].\n}}\n\nThe structure of Earth can be defined in two ways: by mechanical properties such as [[rheology]], or chemically. Mechanically, it can be divided into [[lithosphere]], [[asthenosphere]], [[Mesosphere (mantle)|mesospheric mantle]], [[Earth's outer core|outer core]], and the [[Earth's inner core|inner core]]. Chemically, Earth can be divided into the crust, upper mantle, lower mantle, outer core, and inner core. The geologic component layers of Earth are at the following depths below the surface:<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |last=Montagner |first=Jean-Paul |title=Earth's structure, global |editor-last1=Gupta |editor-first1=Harsh |encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of solid earth geophysics |date=2011 |publisher=Springer Science & Business Media |isbn=9789048187010 |pages=134\u2013154}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!Depth (km) \n!Layer\n|-\n| 0\u201380\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| Lithosphere (locally varies between 5 and 200&nbsp;km)\n|- style=\"background: #FEFEFE;\"\n| 0\u201335\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| ... Crust (locally varies between 5 and 70&nbsp;km)\n|- style=\"background: #FEFEFE;\"\n| 35\u20132,890\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| Mantle\n|- style=\"background: #FEFEFE;\"\n| 80\u2013220\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| ... Asthenosphere\n|- style=\"background: #FEFEFE;\"\n| 410\u2013660\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| ... Transition zone\n|-\n| 35\u2013660\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| ... Upper mantle\n|- style=\"background: #FEFEFE;\"\n| 660\u20132,890\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| ... Lower mantle\n|-\n| 2,740\u20132,890\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| ... D\u2033 layer\n|-\n| 2,890\u20135,150\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| Outer core\n|-\n| 5,150\u20136,360\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| Inner core\n\n|}\n\nThe layering of Earth has been inferred indirectly using the time of travel of refracted and reflected seismic waves created by earthquakes.  The core does not allow shear waves to pass through it, while the speed of travel ([[seismic velocity]]) is different in other layers.  The changes in seismic velocity between different layers causes refraction owing to [[Snell's law]], like light bending as it passes through a prism.  Likewise, reflections are caused by a large increase in seismic velocity and are similar to light reflecting from a mirror.\n\n===Crust===\n{{Main|Earth's crust}}\n\nThe [[Earth's crust]] ranges from {{convert|5|\u2013|70|km}}<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.zmescience.com/other/science-abc/layers-earth-structure/ |title=What are the layers of the Earth? |date=21 August 2018 |access-date=28 June 2019 |first=Mihai |last=Andrei |work=ZME Science}}</ref> in depth and is the outermost layer.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://sciencing.com/earths-structure-crust-inner-core-16911.html |title=Earth's Structure From the Crust to the Inner Core |date=25 April 2017 |access-date=28 June 2019 |first=Lisa |last=Chinn |work=Sciencing |publisher=[[Leaf Group]] Media}}</ref> The thin parts are the [[oceanic crust]], which underlie the ocean basins (5\u201310&nbsp;km) and are composed of dense  ([[mafic]]) iron magnesium [[silicate]] [[Rock (geology)|igneous rocks]], like [[basalt]]. The thicker crust is [[continental crust]], which is less dense and composed of ([[felsic]]) [[sodium]] potassium [[aluminium]] silicate rocks, like [[granite]]. The rocks of the crust fall into two major categories \u2013 sial and sima (Suess, 1831\u20131914). It is estimated that sima starts about 11&nbsp;km below the [[Conrad discontinuity]] (a second order discontinuity). The uppermost mantle together with the crust constitutes the [[lithosphere]]. The crust-mantle boundary occurs as two physically different events. First, there is a discontinuity in the [[seismic wave|seismic]] velocity, which is most commonly known as the [[Mohorovi\u010di\u0107 discontinuity]] or Moho. The cause of the Moho is thought to be a change in rock composition from rocks containing [[feldspar|plagioclase feldspar]] (above) to rocks that contain no feldspars (below). Second, in oceanic crust, there is a [[chemistry|chemical]] discontinuity between [[ultramafic]] cumulates and tectonized [[Peridotite|harzburgites]], which has been observed from deep parts of the oceanic crust that have been [[obduction|obducted]] onto the continental crust and preserved as [[ophiolites|ophiolite sequences]].\n\nMany rocks now making up Earth's crust formed less than 100 million (1{{e|8}}) years ago; however, the oldest known mineral grains are about 4.4 billion (4.4{{e|9}}) years old, indicating that Earth has had a solid crust for at least 4.4 billion years.<ref>[http://spaceflightnow.com/news/n0101/14earthwater/ Breaking News | Oldest rock shows Earth was a hospitable young planet]. Spaceflight Now (2001-01-14). Retrieved on 2012-01-27.</ref>\n\n===Mantle===\n{{Main|Earth's mantle}}\n\n[[File:Mohomap.png|thumb|upright=1.4|World map showing the position of the [[Mohorovi\u010di\u0107 discontinuity|Moho]].]]\n\n[[Earth's mantle]] extends to a depth of 2,890&nbsp;km, making it the thickest layer of Earth.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/trevornace/2016/01/16/layers-of-the-earth-lies-beneath-earths-crust/ |title=Layers Of The Earth: What Lies Beneath Earth's Crust |first=Trevor |last=Nace |date=16 January 2016 |access-date=28 June 2019 |magazine=[[Forbes]]}}</ref> The mantle is divided into upper and [[lower mantle]],<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.nationalgeographic.org/encyclopedia/mantle/ |title=Mantle |first=Jeannie |last=Evers |date=11 August 2015 |access-date=28 June 2019 |journal=[[National Geographic]] |publisher=[[National Geographic Society]]}}</ref> which are separated by the [[Transition zone (Earth)|transition zone]].<ref>{{cite journal |journal=[[Nat Commun]] |volume=9 |date=28 March 2018 |issue=9 |page=1266 |doi=10.1038/s41467-018-03654-6 |pmc=5872023 |pmid=29593266 |title=Compositional heterogeneity near the base of the mantle transition zone beneath Hawaii |first=Chunquan |last=Yu |first2=Elizabeth A. |last2=Day |first3=Maarten V. |last3=de Hoop |first4=Michel |last4=Campillo |first5=Saskia |last5=Goes |first6=Rachel A. |last6=Blythe |first7=Robert D. |last7=van der Hilst |bibcode=2018NatCo...9.1266Y }}</ref> The lowest part of the mantle next to the [[core-mantle boundary]] is known as the D\u2033 (pronounced dee-double-prime) layer.<ref name=\"DDoublePron\">{{cite news |url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2004/03/d-layer-demystified |title=''D'' Layer Demystified |publisher=[[American Association for the Advancement of Science]] |magazine=[[Science News]] |date=24 March 2004 |access-date=5 November 2016 |last=Krieger |first=Kim}}</ref> The [[pressure]] at the bottom of the mantle is \u2248140 G[[pascal (unit)|Pa]] (1.4 M[[Atmosphere (unit)|atm]]).<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.unr.edu/Documents/science/mackay/coring%20the%20earth.pdf |title=Coring the Earth |first=Rachel |last=Dolbier |journal=[[W. M. Keck Earth Science and Mineral Engineering Museum]] |publisher=[[University of Nevada, Reno]] |pages=5 |access-date=28 June 2019}}</ref> The mantle is composed of [[silicate]] rocks that are rich in iron and magnesium relative to the overlying crust.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.universetoday.com/40229/what-is-the-earths-mantle-made-of/ |title=What is the Earth's Mantle Made Of? |date=26 March 2016 |access-date=28 June 2019 |first=Fraser |last=Cain |work=[[Universe Today]]}}</ref> Although solid, the high temperatures within the mantle cause the silicate material to be sufficiently [[Ductility|ductile]] that it can flow on very long timescales.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://sciencing.com/different-properties-asthenosphere-lithosphere-8447830.html |title=The Different Properties of the Asthenosphere & the Lithosphere |date=22 October 2018 |access-date=28 June 2019 |first=Ethan |last=Shaw |work=Sciencing |publisher=[[Leaf Group]] Media}}</ref> [[Convection]] of the mantle is expressed at the surface through the motions of [[tectonic plates]]. As there is intense and increasing pressure as one travels deeper into the mantle, the lower part of the mantle flows less easily than does the [[upper mantle]] (chemical changes within the mantle may also be important). The viscosity of the mantle ranges between 10<sup>21</sup> and 10<sup>24</sup> [[pascal second|Pa\u00b7s]], depending on depth.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Uwe |last=Walzer |first2=Roland |last2=Hendel |first3=John |last3=Baumgardner |author3-link=John Baumgardner |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060826020002/http://www.chemie.uni-jena.de/geowiss/geodyn/poster2.html |title=Mantle Viscosity and the Thickness of the Convective Downwellings |url=http://www.chemie.uni-jena.de/geowiss/geodyn/poster2.html |archive-date=26 August 2006 |access-date=28 June 2019 |journal=[[Los Alamos National Laboratory]] |publisher=[[Universit\u00e4t Heidelberg]]}}</ref> In comparison, the viscosity of water is approximately 10<sup>\u22123</sup> [[pascal second|Pa\u00b7s]] and that of [[Pitch drop experiment|pitch]] is 10<sup>7</sup> Pa\u00b7s. The [[Earth's internal heat budget|source of heat]] that drives [[plate tectonics]] is the primordial heat left over from the planet's formation as well as the radioactive decay of uranium, [[thorium]], and [[potassium]] in Earth's crust and mantle.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://newscenter.lbl.gov/2011/07/17/kamland-geoneutrinos/ |journal=[[Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory]] |publisher=[[University of California, Berkeley]] |title=What Keeps the Earth Cooking? |first=Paul |last=Preuss |date=July 17, 2011 |access-date=28 June 2019 |agency=[[University of California]]}}</ref>\n\n===Core===\n{{Main|Earth's inner core|Earth's outer core}}\n\nThe average density of Earth is\n{{val|5.515|u=[[Gram per cubic centimetre|g/cm<sup>3</sup>]]}}.<ref name=\"NASA\">{{cite web|url=http://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/planetary/factsheet/|title=Planetary Fact Sheet|work=Lunar and Planetary Science|publisher=NASA|accessdate=2 January 2009}}</ref> Because the average density of surface material is only around {{val|3.0|u=g/cm<sup>3</sup>}}, we must conclude that denser materials exist within Earth's core.\nThis result has been known since the [[Schiehallion experiment]], performed in the 1770s.\n[[Charles Hutton]] in his 1778 report concluded that the mean density of the Earth must be about  <math>\\tfrac{9}{5}</math> that of surface rock, concluding that the interior of the Earth must be metallic. Hutton estimated  this metallic portion to occupy some 65% of the diameter of the Earth.<ref name=\"Hutton\">{{Cite journal|last=Hutton|first=C. |date=1778 |title=An Account of the Calculations Made from the Survey and Measures Taken at Schehallien |journal=Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society |volume=68 |pages=689\u2013788 |doi=10.1098/rstl.1778.0034|doi-access=free }}</ref>\nHutton's estimate on the mean density of the Earth was still about 20% too low, at {{val|4.5|u=g/cm<sup>3</sup>}}.\n[[Henry Cavendish]] in his [[Cavendish experiment|torsion balance experiment]] of 1798 found a value of {{val|5.45|u=g/cm<sup>3</sup>}}, within 1% of the modern value.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tretkoff |first1=Ernie |title=June 1798: Cavendish Weighs the World |url=https://www.aps.org/publications/apsnews/200806/physicshistory.cfm |volume=17 |number=6|accessdate=5 June 2018 |work=APS News |publisher=American Physical Society |date=June 2008 |language=en}}</ref>\nSeismic measurements show that the core is divided into two parts, a \"solid\" inner core with a [[radius]] of \u22481,220&nbsp;km<ref>{{Cite journal | first1=Marc | last1=Monnereau | first2=Marie | last2=Calvet | first3=Ludovic | last3=Margerin | first4=Annie | last4=Souriau | title=Lopsided Growth of Earth's Inner Core | journal=Science | date=May 21, 2010 | volume=328 | issue=5981 | pages=1014\u201317 | doi=10.1126/science.1186212 | pmid=20395477|bibcode = 2010Sci...328.1014M }}</ref> and a liquid outer core extending beyond it to a radius of \u22483,400&nbsp;km. The densities are between 9,900 and 12,200&nbsp;kg/m<sup>3</sup> in the outer core and 12,600\u201313,000&nbsp;kg/m<sup>3</sup> in the inner core.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Hazlett, James S. |author2=Monroe, Reed |author3=Wicander, Richard |title=Physical geology : exploring the earth|year=2006|publisher=Thomson|location=Belmont|isbn=978-0-495-01148-4|page=346|edition=6.}}</ref>\n\nThe inner core was discovered in 1936 by [[Inge Lehmann]] and is generally believed to be composed primarily of [[iron]] and some [[nickel]]. Since this layer is able to transmit shear waves (transverse seismic waves), it must be solid.  Experimental evidence has at times been critical of crystal models of the core.<ref>{{Cite journal | first1=Lars | last1=Stixrude | first2=R.E. | last2=Cohen | title=Constraints on the crystalline structure of the inner core: Mechanical instability of BCC iron at high pressure | journal=Geophysical Research Letters | date=January 15, 1995 | volume=22 | issue=2 | pages=125\u201328 | doi=10.1029/94GL02742 |bibcode = 1995GeoRL..22..125S | url=http://discovery.ucl.ac.uk/135995/ }}</ref>  Other experimental studies show a discrepancy under high pressure: diamond anvil (static) studies at core pressures yield melting temperatures that are approximately 2000&nbsp;K below those from shock laser (dynamic) studies.<ref>{{Cite journal | first1=A. | last1=Benuzzi-Mounaix | first2=M. | last2=Koenig | first3=A. | last3=Ravasio | first4=T. | last4=Vinci | title=Laser-driven shock waves for the study of extreme matter states | journal=Plasma Physics and Controlled Fusion |  year=2006 | volume=48 | issue=12B | pages=B347 | doi=10.1088/0741-3335/48/12B/S32 |bibcode = 2006PPCF...48B.347B }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | first1=Bruce A. | last1=Remington | first2=R. Paul | last2=Drake | first3=Dmitri D. | last3=Ryutov | title=Experimental astrophysics with high power lasers and Z pinches | journal=Reviews of Modern Physics | year=2006 | volume=78 | issue=3 | pages=755 | doi=10.1103/RevModPhys.78.755 |bibcode = 2006RvMP...78..755R | url=https://zenodo.org/record/1233971 }}</ref>  The laser studies create plasma,<ref>{{Cite journal | first1=A. | last1=Benuzzi-Mounaix | first2=M. | last2=Koenig | first3=G. | last3=Husar | first4=B. | last4=Faral | title=Absolute equation of state measurements of iron using laser driven shocks | journal=Physics of Plasmas | date=June 2002 | volume=9 | issue=6 | pages=2466 | doi=10.1063/1.1478557 |bibcode = 2002PhPl....9.2466B }}</ref> and the results are suggestive that constraining inner core conditions will depend on whether the inner core is a solid or is a plasma with the density of a solid.  This is an area of active research.\n\nIn early stages of Earth's formation about 4.6 billion years ago, melting would have caused denser substances to sink toward the center in a process called [[planetary differentiation]] (see also the [[iron catastrophe]]), while less-dense materials would have migrated to the [[crust (geology)|crust]]. The core is thus believed to largely be composed of iron (80%), along with [[nickel]] and one or more light elements, whereas other dense elements, such as [[lead]] and [[uranium]], either are too rare to be significant or tend to bind to lighter elements and thus remain in the crust (see [[felsic|felsic materials]]). Some have argued that the inner core may be in the form of a single iron [[crystal]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Schneider |first=Michael | chapter-url=http://www.psc.edu/science/Cohen_Stix/cohen_stix.html |chapter=Crystal at the Center of the Earth |title=Projects in Scientific Computing, 1996|publisher=Pittsburgh Supercomputing Center |date=1996 |accessdate=8 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1126/science.267.5206.1972|title=High-Pressure Elasticity of Iron and Anisotropy of Earth's Inner Core|year=1995|last1=Stixrude|first1=L.|last2=Cohen|first2=R.E.|journal=Science|volume=267|issue=5206|pages=1972\u201375|pmid=17770110|bibcode = 1995Sci...267.1972S }}</ref>\n\nUnder laboratory conditions a sample of iron\u2013nickel alloy was subjected to the corelike pressures by gripping it in a vise between 2 diamond tips ([[diamond anvil cell]]), and then heating to approximately 4000 K. The sample was observed with x-rays, and strongly supported the theory that Earth's inner core was made of giant crystals running north to south.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-14678004 BBC News, \"What is at the centre of the Earth?]. Bbc.co.uk (2011-08-31). Retrieved on 2012-01-27.</ref><ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1126/science.1208265|pmid=22076374|title=Phase Transition of FeO and Stratification in Earth's Outer Core|year=2011|last1=Ozawa|first1=H.|last2=al.|first2=et|journal=Science|volume=334|issue=6057|pages=792\u201394|bibcode = 2011Sci...334..792O }}</ref>\n\nThe liquid outer core surrounds the inner core and is believed to be composed of iron mixed with nickel and trace amounts of lighter elements.\n\nRecent speculation suggests that the innermost part of the core is enriched in [[gold]], [[platinum]] and other [[siderophile element]]s.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Wootton|first1=Anne|year=2006|title=Earth's Inner Fort Knox|url=http://discovermagazine.com/2006/sep/innerfortknox|journal=Discover|volume=27|issue=9|page=18}}</ref>\n\nThe matter that comprises Earth is connected in fundamental ways to matter of certain [[chondrite]] meteorites, and to matter of outer portion of the Sun.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Herndon, J.M.|title=The chemical composition of the interior shells of the Earth|journal= Proc. R. Soc. Lond.|year=1980|volume=A372|pages=149\u201354|jstor=2398362|issue=1748|doi=10.1098/rspa.1980.0106|bibcode=1980RSPSA.372..149H}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Herndon, J.M.|title= Scientific basis of knowledge on Earth's composition|journal=Current Science|year= 2005|volume=88|issue=7|pages=1034\u201337|url=http://nuclearplanet.com/CS50410.pdf}}</ref> There is good reason to believe that Earth is, in the main, like a chondrite meteorite. Beginning as early as 1940, scientists, including [[Francis Birch (geophysicist)|Francis Birch]], built geophysics upon the premise that Earth is like ordinary chondrites, the most common type of meteorite observed impacting Earth, while totally ignoring another, albeit less abundant type, called [[enstatite]] chondrites. The principal difference between the two meteorite types is that enstatite chondrites formed under circumstances of extremely limited available oxygen, leading to certain normally oxyphile elements existing either partially or wholly in the alloy portion that corresponds to the core of Earth.\n\n[[Dynamo theory]] suggests that convection in the outer core, combined with the [[Coriolis effect]], gives rise to [[Earth's magnetic field]]. The solid inner core is too hot to hold a permanent magnetic field (see [[Curie temperature]]) but probably acts to stabilize the magnetic field generated by the liquid outer core. The average magnetic field strength in Earth's outer core is estimated to be 25 Gauss (2.5&nbsp;mT), 50 times stronger than the magnetic field at the surface.<ref>[http://www.science20.com/news_articles/first_measurement_magnetic_field_inside_earths_core First Measurement Of Magnetic Field Inside Earth's Core]. Science20.com. Retrieved on 2012-01-27.</ref><ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1038/nature09643|title=Tidal dissipation and the strength of the Earth's internal magnetic field|year=2010|last1=Buffett|first1=Bruce A.|journal=Nature|volume=468|issue=7326|pages=952\u201394|pmid=21164483|bibcode=2010Natur.468..952B}}</ref>\n\nRecent evidence has suggested that the inner core of Earth may rotate slightly faster than the rest of the planet;<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/08/25/science/25cnd-core.html|work=The New York Times|title=Earth's Core Spins Faster Than the Rest of the Planet|first=Kenneth|last=Chang|date=2005-08-25|accessdate=2010-05-24}}</ref> however, more recent studies in 2011{{which|date=April 2013}} found this hypothesis to be inconclusive. Options remain for the core which may be oscillatory in nature or a chaotic system.{{citation needed|date=April 2013}} In August 2005 a team of [[geophysicist]]s announced in the journal ''[[Science (journal)|Science]]'' that, according to their estimates, Earth's inner core rotates approximately 0.3 to 0.5&nbsp;degrees per year faster relative to the rotation of the surface.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Earth's Inner Core Is Running a Tad Faster Than the Rest of the Planet|doi=10.1126/science.309.5739.1313a|year=2005|last1=Kerr|first1=R.A.|journal=Science|volume=309|issue=5739|pages=1313a|pmid=16123276}}</ref><ref>Chang, Kenneth (26 August 2005) [https://www.nytimes.com/2005/08/26/science/26core.html \"Scientists Say Earth's Center Rotates Faster Than Surface\"] ''The New York Times'' Sec. A, Col. 1, p. 13.</ref>\n\nThe current scientific explanation for [[geothermal gradient|Earth's temperature gradient]] is a combination of heat left over from the planet's initial formation, decay of radioactive elements, and [[Earth's inner core#Growth|freezing of the inner core]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Geological history of Earth]]\n* [[Lehmann discontinuity]]\n* [[Rain-out model]]\n* [[Travel to the Earth's center]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Drollette|first=Daniel |date=October 1996 |title=A Spinning Crystal Ball |journal=Scientific American |volume=275 |number=4 |pages=28\u201333|doi=10.1038/scientificamerican1096-28 |bibcode=1996SciAm.275d..28D }}\n* {{cite journal|last=Kruglinski |first=Susan |title=Journey to the Center of the Earth |journal=Discover |date=June 2007 |url=http://discovermagazine.com/2007/jun/journey-to-the-center-of-the-earth |accessdate=9 July 2016}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Lehmann |first=I |year=1936 |title=Inner Earth |journal=Bur. Cent. Seismol. Int. |volume=14 |pages=3\u201331}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Wegener|first1=Alfred|title=The origin of continents and oceans|date=1966|publisher=Dover Publications|location=New York|isbn=978-0-486-61708-4}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikibooks-inline|Historical Geology|Structure of the Earth}}\n{{Commonscat-inline|Structure of the Earth}}\n* {{YouTube|BsKyEckDRbo|Down To The Earth's Core (HD)}}\n* {{In Our Time|The Earth's Core|b05s3gyv}}\n\n{{Earth}}\n{{Earthsinterior}}\n{{Nature nav}}\n{{Portal bar|Earth sciences|Geophysics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Structure Of The Earth}}\n\n[[Category:Structure of the Earth| ]]\n\ngo in mine instagram @villegas_leo06\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Inner structure of planet Earth, consisting of several concentric spherical layers}}\n\n[[File:Earth poster.svg|thumb|upright=1.4|Structure of Earth]]\n\nThe internal '''structure of Earth''' is layered in spherical shells: an outer [[silicate mineral|silicate]] solid [[crust (geology)|crust]], a highly [[viscosity|viscous]] [[asthenosphere]] and [[Mantle (geology)|mantle]], a liquid [[Earth's outer core|outer core]] that is much less viscous than the mantle, and a solid [[Earth's inner core|inner core]]. Scientific understanding of the internal structure of [[Earth]] is based on observations of [[topography]] and [[bathymetry]], observations of [[rock (geology)|rock]] in [[outcrop]], samples brought to the surface from greater depths by [[volcano|volcanoes]] or volcanic activity, analysis of the [[seismic wave|seismic waves]] that pass through Earth, measurements of the [[Gravity of Earth|gravitational]] and [[Earth's magnetic field|magnetic fields]] of Earth, and experiments with crystalline solids at pressures and temperatures characteristic of Earth's deep interior.\n\n==Mass==\nThe force exerted by [[Earth's gravity]] can be used to calculate its [[mass]]. Astronomers can also calculate [[Earth mass|Earth's mass]] by observing the motion of orbiting [[satellite|satellites]]. Earth's average [[density]] can be determined through gravimetric experiments, which have historically involved [[pendulum|pendulums]].\n\nThe mass of Earth is about {{val|6|e=24|u=kg}}.<ref name=\"AA\">''M''<sub>E</sub> = 5\u00b79722\u00d710<sup>24</sup> kg \u00b1 6\u00d710<sup>20</sup> kg. \"[http://asa.usno.navy.mil/static/files/2016/Astronomical_Constants_2016.pdf 2016 Selected Astronomical Constants]\" in {{citation|title=The Astronomical Almanac Online|url=http://asa.usno.navy.mil/|publisher=[[United States Naval Observatory|USNO]]\u2013[[United Kingdom Hydrographic Office|UKHO]]}}</ref>\n\n==Structure==\n{{multiple image\n | align     = outer most\n| direction = vertical\n | width     = 300\n<!-- Image 1 -->\n | image1    = RadialDensityPREM.jpg\n | alt1      =\n | caption1  = Earth's radial density distribution according to the preliminary reference earth model (PREM).<ref name=\"prem\">{{cite journal|author=A.M. Dziewonski, D.L. Anderson|title=Preliminary reference Earth model |journal=Physics of the Earth and Planetary Interiors|year= 1981|volume=25|issue=4|pages=297\u2013356|url=https://www.cfa.harvard.edu/~lzeng/papers/PREM.pdf|doi=10.1016/0031-9201(81)90046-7|issn=0031-9201|bibcode=1981PEPI...25..297D}}</ref>\n<!-- Image 2 -->\n | image2    = EarthGravityPREM.svg\n | alt2      =\n | caption2  = Earth's gravity according to the preliminary reference earth model (PREM).<ref name=\"prem\"/>  Comparison to approximations using constant and linear density for Earth's interior.\n<!-- Image 3 -->\n | image3    = Earthquake wave paths.svg\n | alt3      =\n | caption3  = Mapping the interior of [[Earth]] with [[earthquake]] waves.\n<!-- Image 4 -->\n | image4    = Slice earth.svg\n | alt4      =\n | caption4  = Schematic view of the interior of Earth. 1. continental crust \u2013 2. oceanic crust \u2013 3. upper mantle \u2013 4. lower mantle \u2013 5. outer core \u2013 6. inner core \u2013 A: [[Mohorovi\u010di\u0107 discontinuity]] \u2013 B: [[Gutenberg Discontinuity]] \u2013 C: [[Earth's inner core|Lehmann\u2013Bullen discontinuity]].\n}}\n\nThe structure of Earth can be defined in two ways: by mechanical properties such as [[rheology]], or chemically. Mechanically, it can be divided into [[lithosphere]], [[asthenosphere]], [[Mesosphere (mantle)|mesospheric mantle]], [[Earth's outer core|outer core]], and the [[Earth's inner core|inner core]]. Chemically, Earth can be divided into the crust, upper mantle, lower mantle, outer core, and inner core. The geologic component layers of Earth are at the following depths below the surface:<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |last=Montagner |first=Jean-Paul |title=Earth's structure, global |editor-last1=Gupta |editor-first1=Harsh |encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of solid earth geophysics |date=2011 |publisher=Springer Science & Business Media |isbn=9789048187010 |pages=134\u2013154}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!Depth (km) \n!Layer\n|-\n| 0\u201380\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| Lithosphere (locally varies between 5 and 200&nbsp;km)\n|- style=\"background: #FEFEFE;\"\n| 0\u201335\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| ... Crust (locally varies between 5 and 70&nbsp;km)\n|- style=\"background: #FEFEFE;\"\n| 35\u20132,890\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| Mantle\n|- style=\"background: #FEFEFE;\"\n| 80\u2013220\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| ... Asthenosphere\n|- style=\"background: #FEFEFE;\"\n| 410\u2013660\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| ... Transition zone\n|-\n| 35\u2013660\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| ... Upper mantle\n|- style=\"background: #FEFEFE;\"\n| 660\u20132,890\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| ... Lower mantle\n|-\n| 2,740\u20132,890\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| ... D\u2033 layer\n|-\n| 2,890\u20135,150\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| Outer core\n|-\n| 5,150\u20136,360\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| Inner core\n\n|}\n\nThe layering of Earth has been inferred indirectly using the time of travel of refracted and reflected seismic waves created by earthquakes.  The core does not allow shear waves to pass through it, while the speed of travel ([[seismic velocity]]) is different in other layers.  The changes in seismic velocity between different layers causes refraction owing to [[Snell's law]], like light bending as it passes through a prism.  Likewise, reflections are caused by a large increase in seismic velocity and are similar to light reflecting from a mirror.\n\n===Crust===\n{{Main|Earth's crust}}\n\nThe [[Earth's crust]] ranges from {{convert|5|\u2013|70|km}}<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.zmescience.com/other/science-abc/layers-earth-structure/ |title=What are the layers of the Earth? |date=21 August 2018 |access-date=28 June 2019 |first=Mihai |last=Andrei |work=ZME Science}}</ref> in depth and is the outermost layer.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://sciencing.com/earths-structure-crust-inner-core-16911.html |title=Earth's Structure From the Crust to the Inner Core |date=25 April 2017 |access-date=28 June 2019 |first=Lisa |last=Chinn |work=Sciencing |publisher=[[Leaf Group]] Media}}</ref> The thin parts are the [[oceanic crust]], which underlie the ocean basins (5\u201310&nbsp;km) and are composed of dense  ([[mafic]]) iron magnesium [[silicate]] [[Rock (geology)|igneous rocks]], like [[basalt]]. The thicker crust is [[continental crust]], which is less dense and composed of ([[felsic]]) [[sodium]] potassium [[aluminium]] silicate rocks, like [[granite]]. The rocks of the crust fall into two major categories \u2013 sial and sima (Suess, 1831\u20131914). It is estimated that sima starts about 11&nbsp;km below the [[Conrad discontinuity]] (a second order discontinuity). The uppermost mantle together with the crust constitutes the [[lithosphere]]. The crust-mantle boundary occurs as two physically different events. First, there is a discontinuity in the [[seismic wave|seismic]] velocity, which is most commonly known as the [[Mohorovi\u010di\u0107 discontinuity]] or Moho. The cause of the Moho is thought to be a change in rock composition from rocks containing [[feldspar|plagioclase feldspar]] (above) to rocks that contain no feldspars (below). Second, in oceanic crust, there is a [[chemistry|chemical]] discontinuity between [[ultramafic]] cumulates and tectonized [[Peridotite|harzburgites]], which has been observed from deep parts of the oceanic crust that have been [[obduction|obducted]] onto the continental crust and preserved as [[ophiolites|ophiolite sequences]].\n\nMany rocks now making up Earth's crust formed less than 100 million (1{{e|8}}) years ago; however, the oldest known mineral grains are about 4.4 billion (4.4{{e|9}}) years old, indicating that Earth has had a solid crust for at least 4.4 billion years.<ref>[http://spaceflightnow.com/news/n0101/14earthwater/ Breaking News | Oldest rock shows Earth was a hospitable young planet]. Spaceflight Now (2001-01-14). Retrieved on 2012-01-27.</ref>\n\n===Mantle===\n{{Main|Earth's mantle}}\n\n[[File:Mohomap.png|thumb|upright=1.4|World map showing the position of the [[Mohorovi\u010di\u0107 discontinuity|Moho]].]]\n\n[[Earth's mantle]] extends to a depth of 2,890&nbsp;km, making it the thickest layer of Earth.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/trevornace/2016/01/16/layers-of-the-earth-lies-beneath-earths-crust/ |title=Layers Of The Earth: What Lies Beneath Earth's Crust |first=Trevor |last=Nace |date=16 January 2016 |access-date=28 June 2019 |magazine=[[Forbes]]}}</ref> The mantle is divided into upper and [[lower mantle]],<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.nationalgeographic.org/encyclopedia/mantle/ |title=Mantle |first=Jeannie |last=Evers |date=11 August 2015 |access-date=28 June 2019 |journal=[[National Geographic]] |publisher=[[National Geographic Society]]}}</ref> which are separated by the [[Transition zone (Earth)|transition zone]].<ref>{{cite journal |journal=[[Nat Commun]] |volume=9 |date=28 March 2018 |issue=9 |page=1266 |doi=10.1038/s41467-018-03654-6 |pmc=5872023 |pmid=29593266 |title=Compositional heterogeneity near the base of the mantle transition zone beneath Hawaii |first=Chunquan |last=Yu |first2=Elizabeth A. |last2=Day |first3=Maarten V. |last3=de Hoop |first4=Michel |last4=Campillo |first5=Saskia |last5=Goes |first6=Rachel A. |last6=Blythe |first7=Robert D. |last7=van der Hilst |bibcode=2018NatCo...9.1266Y }}</ref> The lowest part of the mantle next to the [[core-mantle boundary]] is known as the D\u2033 (pronounced dee-double-prime) layer.<ref name=\"DDoublePron\">{{cite news |url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2004/03/d-layer-demystified |title=''D'' Layer Demystified |publisher=[[American Association for the Advancement of Science]] |magazine=[[Science News]] |date=24 March 2004 |access-date=5 November 2016 |last=Krieger |first=Kim}}</ref> The [[pressure]] at the bottom of the mantle is \u2248140 G[[pascal (unit)|Pa]] (1.4 M[[Atmosphere (unit)|atm]]).<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.unr.edu/Documents/science/mackay/coring%20the%20earth.pdf |title=Coring the Earth |first=Rachel |last=Dolbier |journal=[[W. M. Keck Earth Science and Mineral Engineering Museum]] |publisher=[[University of Nevada, Reno]] |pages=5 |access-date=28 June 2019}}</ref> The mantle is composed of [[silicate]] rocks that are rich in iron and magnesium relative to the overlying crust.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.universetoday.com/40229/what-is-the-earths-mantle-made-of/ |title=What is the Earth's Mantle Made Of? |date=26 March 2016 |access-date=28 June 2019 |first=Fraser |last=Cain |work=[[Universe Today]]}}</ref> Although solid, the high temperatures within the mantle cause the silicate material to be sufficiently [[Ductility|ductile]] that it can flow on very long timescales.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://sciencing.com/different-properties-asthenosphere-lithosphere-8447830.html |title=The Different Properties of the Asthenosphere & the Lithosphere |date=22 October 2018 |access-date=28 June 2019 |first=Ethan |last=Shaw |work=Sciencing |publisher=[[Leaf Group]] Media}}</ref> [[Convection]] of the mantle is expressed at the surface through the motions of [[tectonic plates]]. As there is intense and increasing pressure as one travels deeper into the mantle, the lower part of the mantle flows less easily than does the [[upper mantle]] (chemical changes within the mantle may also be important). The viscosity of the mantle ranges between 10<sup>21</sup> and 10<sup>24</sup> [[pascal second|Pa\u00b7s]], depending on depth.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Uwe |last=Walzer |first2=Roland |last2=Hendel |first3=John |last3=Baumgardner |author3-link=John Baumgardner |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060826020002/http://www.chemie.uni-jena.de/geowiss/geodyn/poster2.html |title=Mantle Viscosity and the Thickness of the Convective Downwellings |url=http://www.chemie.uni-jena.de/geowiss/geodyn/poster2.html |archive-date=26 August 2006 |access-date=28 June 2019 |journal=[[Los Alamos National Laboratory]] |publisher=[[Universit\u00e4t Heidelberg]]}}</ref> In comparison, the viscosity of water is approximately 10<sup>\u22123</sup> [[pascal second|Pa\u00b7s]] and that of [[Pitch drop experiment|pitch]] is 10<sup>7</sup> Pa\u00b7s. The [[Earth's internal heat budget|source of heat]] that drives [[plate tectonics]] is the primordial heat left over from the planet's formation as well as the radioactive decay of uranium, [[thorium]], and [[potassium]] in Earth's crust and mantle.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://newscenter.lbl.gov/2011/07/17/kamland-geoneutrinos/ |journal=[[Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory]] |publisher=[[University of California, Berkeley]] |title=What Keeps the Earth Cooking? |first=Paul |last=Preuss |date=July 17, 2011 |access-date=28 June 2019 |agency=[[University of California]]}}</ref>\n\n===Core===\n{{Main|Earth's inner core|Earth's outer core}}\n\nThe average density of Earth is\n{{val|5.515|u=[[Gram per cubic centimetre|g/cm<sup>3</sup>]]}}.<ref name=\"NASA\">{{cite web|url=http://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/planetary/factsheet/|title=Planetary Fact Sheet|work=Lunar and Planetary Science|publisher=NASA|accessdate=2 January 2009}}</ref> Because the average density of surface material is only around {{val|3.0|u=g/cm<sup>3</sup>}}, we must conclude that denser materials exist within Earth's core.\nThis result has been known since the [[Schiehallion experiment]], performed in the 1770s.\n[[Charles Hutton]] in his 1778 report concluded that the mean density of the Earth must be about  <math>\\tfrac{9}{5}</math> that of surface rock, concluding that the interior of the Earth must be metallic. Hutton estimated  this metallic portion to occupy some 65% of the diameter of the Earth.<ref name=\"Hutton\">{{Cite journal|last=Hutton|first=C. |date=1778 |title=An Account of the Calculations Made from the Survey and Measures Taken at Schehallien |journal=Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society |volume=68 |pages=689\u2013788 |doi=10.1098/rstl.1778.0034|doi-access=free }}</ref>\nHutton's estimate on the mean density of the Earth was still about 20% too low, at {{val|4.5|u=g/cm<sup>3</sup>}}.\n[[Henry Cavendish]] in his [[Cavendish experiment|torsion balance experiment]] of 1798 found a value of {{val|5.45|u=g/cm<sup>3</sup>}}, within 1% of the modern value.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tretkoff |first1=Ernie |title=June 1798: Cavendish Weighs the World |url=https://www.aps.org/publications/apsnews/200806/physicshistory.cfm |volume=17 |number=6|accessdate=5 June 2018 |work=APS News |publisher=American Physical Society |date=June 2008 |language=en}}</ref>\nSeismic measurements show that the core is divided into two parts, a \"solid\" inner core with a [[radius]] of \u22481,220&nbsp;km<ref>{{Cite journal | first1=Marc | last1=Monnereau | first2=Marie | last2=Calvet | first3=Ludovic | last3=Margerin | first4=Annie | last4=Souriau | title=Lopsided Growth of Earth's Inner Core | journal=Science | date=May 21, 2010 | volume=328 | issue=5981 | pages=1014\u201317 | doi=10.1126/science.1186212 | pmid=20395477|bibcode = 2010Sci...328.1014M }}</ref> and a liquid outer core extending beyond it to a radius of \u22483,400&nbsp;km. The densities are between 9,900 and 12,200&nbsp;kg/m<sup>3</sup> in the outer core and 12,600\u201313,000&nbsp;kg/m<sup>3</sup> in the inner core.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Hazlett, James S. |author2=Monroe, Reed |author3=Wicander, Richard |title=Physical geology : exploring the earth|year=2006|publisher=Thomson|location=Belmont|isbn=978-0-495-01148-4|page=346|edition=6.}}</ref>\n\nThe inner core was discovered in 1936 by [[Inge Lehmann]] and is generally believed to be composed primarily of [[iron]] and some [[nickel]]. Since this layer is able to transmit shear waves (transverse seismic waves), it must be solid.  Experimental evidence has at times been critical of crystal models of the core.<ref>{{Cite journal | first1=Lars | last1=Stixrude | first2=R.E. | last2=Cohen | title=Constraints on the crystalline structure of the inner core: Mechanical instability of BCC iron at high pressure | journal=Geophysical Research Letters | date=January 15, 1995 | volume=22 | issue=2 | pages=125\u201328 | doi=10.1029/94GL02742 |bibcode = 1995GeoRL..22..125S | url=http://discovery.ucl.ac.uk/135995/ }}</ref>  Other experimental studies show a discrepancy under high pressure: diamond anvil (static) studies at core pressures yield melting temperatures that are approximately 2000&nbsp;K below those from shock laser (dynamic) studies.<ref>{{Cite journal | first1=A. | last1=Benuzzi-Mounaix | first2=M. | last2=Koenig | first3=A. | last3=Ravasio | first4=T. | last4=Vinci | title=Laser-driven shock waves for the study of extreme matter states | journal=Plasma Physics and Controlled Fusion |  year=2006 | volume=48 | issue=12B | pages=B347 | doi=10.1088/0741-3335/48/12B/S32 |bibcode = 2006PPCF...48B.347B }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | first1=Bruce A. | last1=Remington | first2=R. Paul | last2=Drake | first3=Dmitri D. | last3=Ryutov | title=Experimental astrophysics with high power lasers and Z pinches | journal=Reviews of Modern Physics | year=2006 | volume=78 | issue=3 | pages=755 | doi=10.1103/RevModPhys.78.755 |bibcode = 2006RvMP...78..755R | url=https://zenodo.org/record/1233971 }}</ref>  The laser studies create plasma,<ref>{{Cite journal | first1=A. | last1=Benuzzi-Mounaix | first2=M. | last2=Koenig | first3=G. | last3=Husar | first4=B. | last4=Faral | title=Absolute equation of state measurements of iron using laser driven shocks | journal=Physics of Plasmas | date=June 2002 | volume=9 | issue=6 | pages=2466 | doi=10.1063/1.1478557 |bibcode = 2002PhPl....9.2466B }}</ref> and the results are suggestive that constraining inner core conditions will depend on whether the inner core is a solid or is a plasma with the density of a solid.  This is an area of active research.\n\nIn early stages of Earth's formation about 4.6 billion years ago, melting would have caused denser substances to sink toward the center in a process called [[planetary differentiation]] (see also the [[iron catastrophe]]), while less-dense materials would have migrated to the [[crust (geology)|crust]]. The core is thus believed to largely be composed of iron (80%), along with [[nickel]] and one or more light elements, whereas other dense elements, such as [[lead]] and [[uranium]], either are too rare to be significant or tend to bind to lighter elements and thus remain in the crust (see [[felsic|felsic materials]]). Some have argued that the inner core may be in the form of a single iron [[crystal]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Schneider |first=Michael | chapter-url=http://www.psc.edu/science/Cohen_Stix/cohen_stix.html |chapter=Crystal at the Center of the Earth |title=Projects in Scientific Computing, 1996|publisher=Pittsburgh Supercomputing Center |date=1996 |accessdate=8 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1126/science.267.5206.1972|title=High-Pressure Elasticity of Iron and Anisotropy of Earth's Inner Core|year=1995|last1=Stixrude|first1=L.|last2=Cohen|first2=R.E.|journal=Science|volume=267|issue=5206|pages=1972\u201375|pmid=17770110|bibcode = 1995Sci...267.1972S }}</ref>\n\nUnder laboratory conditions a sample of iron\u2013nickel alloy was subjected to the corelike pressures by gripping it in a vise between 2 diamond tips ([[diamond anvil cell]]), and then heating to approximately 4000 K. The sample was observed with x-rays, and strongly supported the theory that Earth's inner core was made of giant crystals running north to south.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-14678004 BBC News, \"What is at the centre of the Earth?]. Bbc.co.uk (2011-08-31). Retrieved on 2012-01-27.</ref><ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1126/science.1208265|pmid=22076374|title=Phase Transition of FeO and Stratification in Earth's Outer Core|year=2011|last1=Ozawa|first1=H.|last2=al.|first2=et|journal=Science|volume=334|issue=6057|pages=792\u201394|bibcode = 2011Sci...334..792O }}</ref>\n\nThe liquid outer core surrounds the inner core and is believed to be composed of iron mixed with nickel and trace amounts of lighter elements.\n\nRecent speculation suggests that the innermost part of the core is enriched in [[gold]], [[platinum]] and other [[siderophile element]]s.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Wootton|first1=Anne|year=2006|title=Earth's Inner Fort Knox|url=http://discovermagazine.com/2006/sep/innerfortknox|journal=Discover|volume=27|issue=9|page=18}}</ref>\n\nThe matter that comprises Earth is connected in fundamental ways to matter of certain [[chondrite]] meteorites, and to matter of outer portion of the Sun.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Herndon, J.M.|title=The chemical composition of the interior shells of the Earth|journal= Proc. R. Soc. Lond.|year=1980|volume=A372|pages=149\u201354|jstor=2398362|issue=1748|doi=10.1098/rspa.1980.0106|bibcode=1980RSPSA.372..149H}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Herndon, J.M.|title= Scientific basis of knowledge on Earth's composition|journal=Current Science|year= 2005|volume=88|issue=7|pages=1034\u201337|url=http://nuclearplanet.com/CS50410.pdf}}</ref> There is good reason to believe that Earth is, in the main, like a chondrite meteorite. Beginning as early as 1940, scientists, including [[Francis Birch (geophysicist)|Francis Birch]], built geophysics upon the premise that Earth is like ordinary chondrites, the most common type of meteorite observed impacting Earth, while totally ignoring another, albeit less abundant type, called [[enstatite]] chondrites. The principal difference between the two meteorite types is that enstatite chondrites formed under circumstances of extremely limited available oxygen, leading to certain normally oxyphile elements existing either partially or wholly in the alloy portion that corresponds to the core of Earth.\n\n[[Dynamo theory]] suggests that convection in the outer core, combined with the [[Coriolis effect]], gives rise to [[Earth's magnetic field]]. The solid inner core is too hot to hold a permanent magnetic field (see [[Curie temperature]]) but probably acts to stabilize the magnetic field generated by the liquid outer core. The average magnetic field strength in Earth's outer core is estimated to be 25 Gauss (2.5&nbsp;mT), 50 times stronger than the magnetic field at the surface.<ref>[http://www.science20.com/news_articles/first_measurement_magnetic_field_inside_earths_core First Measurement Of Magnetic Field Inside Earth's Core]. Science20.com. Retrieved on 2012-01-27.</ref><ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1038/nature09643|title=Tidal dissipation and the strength of the Earth's internal magnetic field|year=2010|last1=Buffett|first1=Bruce A.|journal=Nature|volume=468|issue=7326|pages=952\u201394|pmid=21164483|bibcode=2010Natur.468..952B}}</ref>\n\nRecent evidence has suggested that the inner core of Earth may rotate slightly faster than the rest of the planet;<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/08/25/science/25cnd-core.html|work=The New York Times|title=Earth's Core Spins Faster Than the Rest of the Planet|first=Kenneth|last=Chang|date=2005-08-25|accessdate=2010-05-24}}</ref> however, more recent studies in 2011{{which|date=April 2013}} found this hypothesis to be inconclusive. Options remain for the core which may be oscillatory in nature or a chaotic system.{{citation needed|date=April 2013}} In August 2005 a team of [[geophysicist]]s announced in the journal ''[[Science (journal)|Science]]'' that, according to their estimates, Earth's inner core rotates approximately 0.3 to 0.5&nbsp;degrees per year faster relative to the rotation of the surface.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Earth's Inner Core Is Running a Tad Faster Than the Rest of the Planet|doi=10.1126/science.309.5739.1313a|year=2005|last1=Kerr|first1=R.A.|journal=Science|volume=309|issue=5739|pages=1313a|pmid=16123276}}</ref><ref>Chang, Kenneth (26 August 2005) [https://www.nytimes.com/2005/08/26/science/26core.html \"Scientists Say Earth's Center Rotates Faster Than Surface\"] ''The New York Times'' Sec. A, Col. 1, p. 13.</ref>\n\nThe current scientific explanation for [[geothermal gradient|Earth's temperature gradient]] is a combination of heat left over from the planet's initial formation, decay of radioactive elements, and [[Earth's inner core#Growth|freezing of the inner core]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Geological history of Earth]]\n* [[Lehmann discontinuity]]\n* [[Rain-out model]]\n* [[Travel to the Earth's center]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Drollette|first=Daniel |date=October 1996 |title=A Spinning Crystal Ball |journal=Scientific American |volume=275 |number=4 |pages=28\u201333|doi=10.1038/scientificamerican1096-28 |bibcode=1996SciAm.275d..28D }}\n* {{cite journal|last=Kruglinski |first=Susan |title=Journey to the Center of the Earth |journal=Discover |date=June 2007 |url=http://discovermagazine.com/2007/jun/journey-to-the-center-of-the-earth |accessdate=9 July 2016}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Lehmann |first=I |year=1936 |title=Inner Earth |journal=Bur. Cent. Seismol. Int. |volume=14 |pages=3\u201331}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Wegener|first1=Alfred|title=The origin of continents and oceans|date=1966|publisher=Dover Publications|location=New York|isbn=978-0-486-61708-4}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikibooks-inline|Historical Geology|Structure of the Earth}}\n{{Commonscat-inline|Structure of the Earth}}\n* {{YouTube|BsKyEckDRbo|Down To The Earth's Core (HD)}}\n* {{In Our Time|The Earth's Core|b05s3gyv}}\n\n{{Earth}}\n{{Earthsinterior}}\n{{Nature nav}}\n{{Portal bar|Earth sciences|Geophysics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Structure Of The Earth}}\n\n[[Category:Structure of the Earth| ]]\n", "name_user": "45.170.196.70", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Structure_of_Earth"}
{"title_page": "Sailing yacht", "text_new": "{{multiple image|direction=vertical|image1=2013_Ahmanson_Cup_Regatta_yacht_Zapata_II_b_photo_D_Ramey_Logan.jpg|caption1=''Zapata II'', a 50&nbsp;ft cruising yacht|image2=60feet IMOCA SAFRAN 01.JPG|caption2=A 60&nbsp;ft [[IMOCA 60|IMOCA]] ocean racing yacht}}\n[[Image:Aerial view Yacht Harbour Residence Rostock Yachthafenresidenz Hohe D\u00fcne 1.jpg|thumb|upright|View of a yacht club, [[Rostock]]]]\n\nA '''sailing yacht''' (US ship prefixes SY or S/Y), is a leisure craft that uses sails as its primary means of propulsion. A yacht may be a sail or power vessel used for pleasure, cruising, or racing.<ref name=\"Webster\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/yacht|title=Definition of YACHT|website=www.merriam-webster.com|language=en|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dictionary.cambridge.org/us/dictionary/english/yacht|title=YACHT {{!}} definition in the Cambridge English Dictionary|website=dictionary.cambridge.org|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.collinsdictionary.com/us/dictionary/english/yacht|title=Yacht definition and meaning {{!}} Collins English Dictionary|website=www.collinsdictionary.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> There is no standard definition, so the term applies here to sailing vessels that have a cabin with amenities that accommodate overnight use. To be termed a \"yacht\", as opposed to a \"boat\", such a vessel is likely to be at least {{Convert|33|ft|m|abbr=}} in length and have been judged to have good aesthetic qualities.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.boats.com/on-the-water/when-is-a-boat-also-a-yacht/|title=When is a Boat Also a Yacht? - boats.com|last=Kavin|first=Kim|date=June 4, 2018|website=www.boats.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> [[Sailboat|Sailboats]] that don't accommodate overnight use or are smaller than {{Convert|30|ft|m|abbr=}} are not universally called yachts. Sailing yachts in excess of {{Convert|40|m|ft|abbr=|order=flip}} are generally considered to be [[Superyacht|superyachts]].<ref name=\"Perry\">{{Cite book|last=Perry, Julie|title=Insiders' guide to becoming a yacht stewardess : confessions from my years afloat with the rich and famous|date=August 2013|isbn=978-1-61448-786-9|edition=Second|location=New York|oclc=859781233}}</ref>\n\nSailing [[yacht]]s are actively used in sport and are among categories recognized by the governing body of sailing sports, [[World Sailing]].<ref>[http://www.sailing.org/classes/#isaf_sliding_tab_item_classes_index_yacht World Sailing classes of yachts].</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe history of pleasure boats begins with rowed craft in Pharaonic Egyptian times. The history of sailing yachts begins in Europe in the beginning of the 1600s with the building of a pleasure vessel for the son of [[James VI and I|King James I of England]]. Pleasure vessels acquired the name ''yacht'' after the time of [[Charles II of England|Charles II]], who spent time exiled in Europe and visited the Netherlands, where a variety of yachts (''jaghts'' in Dutch) were already well-developed as pleasure boats for the elite classes since the beginning of the 17th century. Upon his restoration to the English crown, Charles commissioned a series of royal yachts, which included at least one experimental [[catamaran]]. The first recorded yacht race between two vessels occurred in 1661, followed by the first open sailing competition in 1663 in English waters.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Herreshoff|first=L. Francis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q4RONp_1mrMC&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&dq=history+of+sailing+yachts&hl=en|title=The Golden Age of Yachting|date=2007|publisher=Sheridan House, Inc.|year=|isbn=978-1-57409-251-6|location=|pages=19-25|language=en}}</ref>\n\nStarting in 1739, England found itself in a series of wars\u2014a period that saw a decline in yachting. In Ireland, however, the gentry enjoyed yachting and founded the first yacht club in Cork as the Cork Harbor Water Club in 1720. English yacht racing continued among the English gentry who founded England's oldest yacht club in 1775 to support a fleet at [[Cumberland]]. With maritime peace, starting in 1815, came a resurgence of interest in yachting. Boatbuilders, who had been making fast vessels both for smugglers and the government [[Cutter (boat)|revenue cutters]], turned their skills again to yachts.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Evolution of design ===\nThe fast yachts of the early 19th century were typically [[lugger]]s, [[schooner]]s, or [[sloop]]s with [[fore-and-aft rig]]s. By the 1850s, yachts featured large sail areas, a narrow beam, and a deeper draft than was customary until then. Racing between yachts owned by wealthy patrons was common, with large wagers at stake. The [[America's Cup]] arose out of a contest between the yacht, ''[[America (yacht)|America]]'', and its English competitors. Both countries had rules by which to rate yachts, the English by tonnage and the American by length.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nEnglish and American design philosophies for sailing yachts diverged in the early 1800s: the English favoring a narrow [[Beam (nautical)|beam]] (width) and a deep-draft keel and the Americans favoring a broad beam and a shallow draft with a moveable centerboard to provide lateral resistance and righting moment. In 1851, when the yacht ''America'' crossed to England, the two design philosophies were converging back towards each other. ''America's'' pointed, convex bow and maximum beam, placed aft, influenced British designs, thanks to her racing successes against the British competition. American yachtsmen, in turn, found that their shallow \"skimming-dish\" designs weren't faster or safer than the visiting English yachts.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Doane, Charles J.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/551161085|title=The modern cruising sailboat : a complete guide to its design, construction, and outfitting|date=2010|publisher=International Marine|isbn=978-0-07-163700-8|location=Camden, Me.|oclc=551161085}}</ref>\n\nBy the turn of the 20th century, racing yachts featured long overhangs, fore and aft, and a narrow, deep keel by historic standards. Along the way, yacht designers discovered that handicapping rules based on tonnage or length were not good indicators of performance, although they remained a basis for taxation in the two home countries.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Cruising yachts ===\nThe prevalent purpose of yachting under sail in the 19th was racing. Boats would cross the Atlantic to engage the yachts of other owners in contests of speed. Cruising was the provenance of the most wealthy in large, luxurious yachts that had reliable auxiliary power or were solely steam-powered yachts.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nEarly explorers in smaller sailing craft wrote of their experiences cruising the lakes and canals of Europe in a sailing canoe ([[John MacGregor (sportsman)|John MacGregor]]) and the near-shore waters of England and Scotland in a {{Convert|20|ft|m|abbr=|adj=on}} [[Cutter (boat)|cutter]] (R.T. McMullen). In the late 1800s some cruising adventurers converted fishing vessels and pilot boats into cruising boats. The most note of these was [[Joshua Slocum|Joshua Slocum's]] ''[[Spray (sailing vessel)|Spray]]'', a converted work boat in which he accomplished the first single-handed circumnavigation.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn the 20th century, cruising yacht design evolved past the handicapping rules-based designs of the 19th century towards more sea-kindly hull designs. In the 1930s yacht hulls were designed with a \"fisherman\" underbody, whereby the slope of the bow continued to the fullest extent of the draft and then carried horizontally aft. Noted yacht designers, such as [[John Alden (naval architect)|John Alden]] and [[William Starling Burgess|Starling Burgess]] employed this configuration. Starting in the 1920s several new rating rules were devised by the [[Cruising Club of America]] and the [[Royal Ocean Racing Club]] in order to handicap yachts of different designs that were expected to compete against one another. Successful designers of this era were [[Olin Stephens]], [[Philip Rhodes]], Aage Nielson, and C. Raymond Hunt. The International Offshore Racing (IOR) rule supplanted the previous rules in 1970 to provide a fairer basis for handicapping racing yachts. This rule promoted the use of fin keels and blade rudders. This rule was augmented with the International Measurement System (IMS) to assure safe designs for extreme conditions, following the disastrous [[1979 Fastnet race|1979 Fastnet Race]] in which only 86 of the 303 participants finished owing to failed equipment and loss of 19 lives and five boats.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Technical Committee|first=Cruising Club of America|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/14377959|title=Desirable and undesirable characteristics of offshore yachts|date=1987|publisher=W.W. Norton|others=|year=|isbn=0-393-03311-2|editor-last=Rousmaniere|editor-first=John|location=New York|pages=23-39|oclc=14377959}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Larsson, Lars.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/864139368|title=Principles of yacht design|others=Eliasson, Rolf E.|isbn=978-1-4729-0555-0|edition=Third edition|location=London|oclc=864139368}}</ref>\n\n==Cruising==\n{{Under construction}}\n\nCruising yachts may be designed for near-shore use or for passage-making. They may also be raced, but they are designed and built with the comfort and amenities necessary for overnight voyages.\n\n=== Categories ===\nCruising sailboats share the common attribute of providing overnight accommodations. They may be classified as small (easy to haul behind a trailer),<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=Henkel|first=Steve|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eQt-0KvDJJkC&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&dq=Cruising+sailboat&hl=en|title=The Sailor's Book of Small Cruising Sailboats: Reviews and Comparisons of 360 Boats Under 26 Feet|date=2010-01-15|publisher=McGraw Hill Professional|isbn=978-0-07-173694-7|language=en}}</ref> near-shore<ref name=\":1\" /> and off-shore.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Committee|first=Cruising Club of America Technical|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pee1lKH4J4kC&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&dq=Cruising+sailboat&hl=en|title=Desirable and Undesirable Characteristics of Offshore Yachts|date=1987|publisher=W. W. Norton & Company|isbn=978-0-393-03311-3|language=en}}</ref> Multihull sailing yachts are a category, apart.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|last=Judges panel|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7Mo9Kw2sX9sC&pg=PA147&dq=cruising+sailing+yacht&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiN6rro5PXoAhWlhHIEHQ9qAgsQ6AEwBHoECAEQAg#v=onepage&q=Category&f=false|title=Boats of the Year|date=March 1997|work=Cruising World|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=90-100|language=en}}</ref>\n\n*'''Small''' \u2013 Small sailing yachts that are readily towed by a car are generally shorter than {{Convert|25|ft|m|abbr=}}, length overall and weigh less than {{Convert|5,000|lb|kg|abbr=}}.<ref name=\":2\" /> They are sometimes called \"pocket cruisers\" and may be trimarans with folding [[Outrigger|outriggers]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Warren|first=Quentin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7Mo9Kw2sX9sC&pg=PA147&dq=cruising+sailing+yacht&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiN6rro5PXoAhWlhHIEHQ9qAgsQ6AEwBHoECAEQAg#v=onepage&q=pocket%20cruiser&f=false|title=Dragon 920 Swing Wing|date=July 1997|work=Cruising World|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=76|language=en}}</ref> Considerations for their design include: a shallow draft for launching, likely supplemented by a centerboard for performance under sail, sail area/displacement ratio as a measure of stability, displacement/length ratio as a measure of efficiency in propelling it through the water, and by its interior space\u2014both interior height and volume.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n*'''Near-shore''' \u2013 Near-shore cruising sailboats typically range in size from {{Convert|33-45|ft|m|abbr=}} length overall.<ref name=\":4\" /> The [[Royal Yachting Association]] has two design categories for yachts used in this context: \"C\" yachts are fit for wind force 6\u2014{{Convert|27|kn|m/s|abbr=}}\u2014and {{Convert|2|m|ft|abbr=|order=flip|adj=on}} wave heights. \"D\" yachts are fit for wind force 4\u2014{{Convert|16|kn|m/s|abbr=}}\u2014and {{Convert|0.5|m|ft|abbr=|order=flip|adj=on}} maximum wave heights.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|last=Association|first=Royal Yachting|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oGqADwAAQBAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&dq=sailing+yacht+insurance+categories&hl=en|title=RYA Stability & Buoyancy (E-G23)|date=2018-12-20|publisher=Royal Yachting Association|language=en}}</ref>\n\n*'''Offshore''' \u2013 Offshore cruising sailboats typically exceed {{Convert|45|ft|m|abbr=}} length overall.<ref name=\":4\" /> The Royal Yachting Association has two design categories for yachts used in this context: \"A\" yachts are fit for conditions that <u>exceed</u> wind force 8\u2014{{Convert|40|kn|m/s|abbr=}}\u2014and {{Convert|4|m|ft|abbr=|order=flip|adj=on}} wave heights. \"B\" yachts are fit for <u>up to</u> that threshold.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n=== Design ===\nCatamarans offer tradeoffs as cruising sailboats, compared with [[Monohull|monohulls]]. Their advantages include greater: stability, speed, living space, and shallower draft. Their drawbacks include: greater expenses, greater [[windage]], more difficult tacking under sail, less load capacity, and more maneuvering room required because of their broad beam. They come with a variety of sleeping accommodations and bridge-deck configurations. <ref>{{Cite book|last=Tarjan, Gregor.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/233534126|title=Catamarans : the complete guide for cruising sailors|date=2008|publisher=International Marine|isbn=978-0-07-159622-0|location=Camden, Me.|oclc=233534126}}</ref>\n\n=== Construction ===\n\n=== Rigs ===\n\n=== Gear ===\n\n=== Accommodations ===\n\n=== Systems ===\n\n==Racing==\n{{Under construction|section=Description|placedby=HopsonRoad}}\nWorld Sailing recognizes nine classes of racing yacht:<ref>[http://www.sailing.org/classes/#isaf_sliding_tab_item_classes_index_yacht World Sailing classes of yachts].</ref>\n\n#[[Class40]]\n#[[Farr 30]]\n#[[Farr 40]]\n#[[International Maxi Association]]\n#[[J/111]]\n#[[IMOCA 60]]\n#[[Soto 40]]\n#[[Swan 45]]\n#[[Swan 60]]\n#[[TP 52]]\n#[[X-35 (yacht)|X-35]]\n#[[X-41 (yacht)|X-41]]\n\n==See also==\n{{commonscat-inline|Sailing yachts}}\n*[[Dinghy sailing]]\n*[[International class]]\n*[[List of large sailing yachts]]\n*[[Skiff|Sailing skiff]]\n{{International Sailing Federation Classes}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n[[Category:Sailing yachts]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple image|direction=vertical|image1=2013_Ahmanson_Cup_Regatta_yacht_Zapata_II_b_photo_D_Ramey_Logan.jpg|caption1=''Zapata II'', a 50&nbsp;ft cruising yacht|image2=60feet IMOCA SAFRAN 01.JPG|caption2=A 60&nbsp;ft [[IMOCA 60|IMOCA]] ocean racing yacht}}\n[[Image:Aerial view Yacht Harbour Residence Rostock Yachthafenresidenz Hohe D\u00fcne 1.jpg|thumb|upright|View of a yacht club, [[Rostock]]]]\n\nA '''sailing yacht''' (US ship prefixes SY or S/Y), is a leisure craft that uses sails as its primary means of propulsion. A yacht may be a sail or power vessel used for pleasure, cruising, or racing.<ref name=\"Webster\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/yacht|title=Definition of YACHT|website=www.merriam-webster.com|language=en|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dictionary.cambridge.org/us/dictionary/english/yacht|title=YACHT {{!}} definition in the Cambridge English Dictionary|website=dictionary.cambridge.org|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.collinsdictionary.com/us/dictionary/english/yacht|title=Yacht definition and meaning {{!}} Collins English Dictionary|website=www.collinsdictionary.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> There is no standard definition, so the term applies here to sailing vessels that have a cabin with amenities that accommodate overnight use. To be termed a \"yacht\", as opposed to a \"boat\", such a vessel is likely to be at least {{Convert|33|ft|m|abbr=}} in length and have been judged to have good aesthetic qualities.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.boats.com/on-the-water/when-is-a-boat-also-a-yacht/|title=When is a Boat Also a Yacht? - boats.com|last=Kavin|first=Kim|date=June 4, 2018|website=www.boats.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> [[Sailboat|Sailboats]] that don't accommodate overnight use or are smaller than {{Convert|30|ft|m|abbr=}} are not universally called yachts. Sailing yachts in excess of {{Convert|40|m|ft|abbr=|order=flip}} are generally considered to be [[Superyacht|superyachts]].<ref name=\"Perry\">{{Cite book|last=Perry, Julie|title=Insiders' guide to becoming a yacht stewardess : confessions from my years afloat with the rich and famous|date=August 2013|isbn=978-1-61448-786-9|edition=Second|location=New York|oclc=859781233}}</ref>\n\nSailing [[yacht]]s are actively used in sport and are among categories recognized by the governing body of sailing sports, [[World Sailing]].<ref>[http://www.sailing.org/classes/#isaf_sliding_tab_item_classes_index_yacht World Sailing classes of yachts].</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe history of pleasure boats begins with rowed craft in Pharaonic Egyptian times. The history of sailing yachts begins in Europe in the beginning of the 1600s with the building of a pleasure vessel for the son of [[James VI and I|King James I of England]]. Pleasure vessels acquired the name ''yacht'' after the time of [[Charles II of England|Charles II]], who spent time exiled in Europe and visited the Netherlands, where a variety of yachts (''jaghts'' in Dutch) were already well-developed as pleasure boats for the elite classes since the beginning of the 17th century. Upon his restoration to the English crown, Charles commissioned a series of royal yachts, which included at least one experimental [[catamaran]]. The first recorded yacht race between two vessels occurred in 1661, followed by the first open sailing competition in 1663 in English waters.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Herreshoff|first=L. Francis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q4RONp_1mrMC&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&dq=history+of+sailing+yachts&hl=en|title=The Golden Age of Yachting|date=2007|publisher=Sheridan House, Inc.|year=|isbn=978-1-57409-251-6|location=|pages=19-25|language=en}}</ref>\n\nStarting in 1739, England found itself in a series of wars\u2014a period that saw a decline in yachting. In Ireland, however, the gentry enjoyed yachting and founded the first yacht club in Cork as the Cork Harbor Water Club in 1720. English yacht racing continued among the English gentry who founded England's oldest yacht club in 1775 to support a fleet at [[Cumberland]]. With maritime peace, starting in 1815, came a resurgence of interest in yachting. Boatbuilders, who had been making fast vessels both for smugglers and the government [[Cutter (boat)|revenue cutters]], turned their skills again to yachts.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Evolution of design ===\nThe fast yachts of the early 19th century were typically [[lugger]]s, [[schooner]]s, or [[sloop]]s with [[fore-and-aft rig]]s. By the 1850s, yachts featured large sail areas, a narrow beam, and a deeper draft than was customary until then. Racing between yachts owned by wealthy patrons was common, with large wagers at stake. The [[America's Cup]] arose out of a contest between the yacht, ''[[America (yacht)|America]]'', and its English competitors. Both countries had rules by which to rate yachts, the English by tonnage and the American by length.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nEnglish and American design philosophies for sailing yachts diverged in the early 1800s: the English favoring a narrow [[Beam (nautical)|beam]] (width) and a deep-draft keel and the Americans favoring a broad beam and a shallow draft with a moveable centerboard to provide lateral resistance and righting moment. In 1851, when the yacht ''America'' crossed to England, the two design philosophies were converging back towards each other. ''America's'' pointed, convex bow and maximum beam, placed aft, influenced British designs, thanks to her racing successes against the British competition. American yachtsmen, in turn, found that their shallow \"skimming-dish\" designs weren't faster or safer than the visiting English yachts.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Doane, Charles J.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/551161085|title=The modern cruising sailboat : a complete guide to its design, construction, and outfitting|date=2010|publisher=International Marine|isbn=978-0-07-163700-8|location=Camden, Me.|oclc=551161085}}</ref>\n\nBy the turn of the 20th century, racing yachts featured long overhangs, fore and aft, and a narrow, deep keel by historic standards. Along the way, yacht designers discovered that handicapping rules based on tonnage or length were not good indicators of performance, although they remained a basis for taxation in the two home countries.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Cruising yachts ===\nThe prevalent purpose of yachting under sail in the 19th was racing. Boats would cross the Atlantic to engage the yachts of other owners in contests of speed. Cruising was the provenance of the most wealthy in large, luxurious yachts that had reliable auxiliary power or were solely steam-powered yachts.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nEarly explorers in smaller sailing craft wrote of their experiences cruising the lakes and canals of Europe in a sailing canoe ([[John MacGregor (sportsman)|John MacGregor]]) and the near-shore waters of England and Scotland in a {{Convert|20|ft|m|abbr=|adj=on}} [[Cutter (boat)|cutter]] (R.T. McMullen). In the late 1800s some cruising adventurers converted fishing vessels and pilot boats into cruising boats. The most note of these was [[Joshua Slocum|Joshua Slocum's]] ''[[Spray (sailing vessel)|Spray]]'', a converted work boat in which he accomplished the first single-handed circumnavigation.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn the 20th century, cruising yacht design evolved past the handicapping rules-based designs of the 19th century towards more sea-kindly hull designs. In the 1930s yacht hulls were designed with a \"fisherman\" underbody, whereby the slope of the bow continued to the fullest extent of the draft and then carried horizontally aft. Noted yacht designers, such as [[John Alden (naval architect)|John Alden]] and [[William Starling Burgess|Starling Burgess]] employed this configuration. Starting in the 1920s several new rating rules were devised by the [[Cruising Club of America]] and the [[Royal Ocean Racing Club]] in order to handicap yachts of different designs that were expected to compete against one another. Successful designers of this era were [[Olin Stephens]], [[Philip Rhodes]], Aage Nielson, and C. Raymond Hunt. The International Offshore Racing (IOR) rule supplanted the previous rules in 1970 to provide a fairer basis for handicapping racing yachts. This rule promoted the use of fin keels and blade rudders. This rule was augmented with the International Measurement System (IMS) to assure safe designs for extreme conditions, following the disastrous [[1979 Fastnet race|1979 Fastnet Race]] in which only 86 of the 303 participants finished owing to failed equipment and loss of 19 lives and five boats.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Technical Committee|first=Cruising Club of America|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/14377959|title=Desirable and undesirable characteristics of offshore yachts|date=1987|publisher=W.W. Norton|others=|year=|isbn=0-393-03311-2|editor-last=Rousmaniere|editor-first=John|location=New York|pages=23-39|oclc=14377959}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Larsson, Lars.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/864139368|title=Principles of yacht design|others=Eliasson, Rolf E.|isbn=978-1-4729-0555-0|edition=Third edition|location=London|oclc=864139368}}</ref>\n\n==Cruising==\n{{Under construction}}\n\nCruising yachts may be designed for near-shore use or for passage-making. They may also be raced, but they are designed and built with the comfort and amenities necessary for overnight voyages.\n\n=== Categories ===\nCruising sailboats share the common attribute of providing overnight accommodations. They may be classified as small (easy to haul behind a trailer),<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=Henkel|first=Steve|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eQt-0KvDJJkC&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&dq=Cruising+sailboat&hl=en|title=The Sailor's Book of Small Cruising Sailboats: Reviews and Comparisons of 360 Boats Under 26 Feet|date=2010-01-15|publisher=McGraw Hill Professional|isbn=978-0-07-173694-7|language=en}}</ref> near-shore<ref name=\":1\" /> and off-shore.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Committee|first=Cruising Club of America Technical|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pee1lKH4J4kC&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&dq=Cruising+sailboat&hl=en|title=Desirable and Undesirable Characteristics of Offshore Yachts|date=1987|publisher=W. W. Norton & Company|isbn=978-0-393-03311-3|language=en}}</ref> Multihull sailing yachts are a category, apart.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|last=Judges panel|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7Mo9Kw2sX9sC&pg=PA147&dq=cruising+sailing+yacht&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiN6rro5PXoAhWlhHIEHQ9qAgsQ6AEwBHoECAEQAg#v=onepage&q=Category&f=false|title=Boats of the Year|date=March 1997|work=Cruising World|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=90-100|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==== Small ====\nSmall sailing yachts that are readily towed by a car are generally shorter than {{Convert|25|ft|m|abbr=}}, length overall and weigh less than {{Convert|5,000|lb|kg|abbr=}}.<ref name=\":2\" /> They are sometimes called \"pocket cruisers\" and may be trimarans with folding [[Outrigger|outriggers]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Warren|first=Quentin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7Mo9Kw2sX9sC&pg=PA147&dq=cruising+sailing+yacht&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiN6rro5PXoAhWlhHIEHQ9qAgsQ6AEwBHoECAEQAg#v=onepage&q=pocket%20cruiser&f=false|title=Dragon 920 Swing Wing|date=July 1997|work=Cruising World|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=76|language=en}}</ref> Considerations for their design include: a shallow draft for launching, likely supplemented by a centerboard for performance under sail, sail area/displacement ratio as a measure of stability, displacement/length ratio as a measure of efficiency in propelling it through the water, and by its interior space\u2014both interior height and volume.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==== Near-shore ====\nNear-shore cruising sailboats typically range in size from {{Convert|33-45|ft|m|abbr=}} length overall.<ref name=\":4\" /> The [[Royal Yachting Association]] has two design categories for yachts used in this context: \"C\" yachts are fit for wind force 6\u2014{{Convert|27|kn|m/s|abbr=}}\u2014and {{Convert|2|m|ft|abbr=|order=flip|adj=on}} wave heights. \"D\" yachts are fit for wind force 4\u2014{{Convert|16|kn|m/s|abbr=}}\u2014and {{Convert|0.5|m|ft|abbr=|order=flip|adj=on}} maximum wave heights.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|last=Association|first=Royal Yachting|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oGqADwAAQBAJ&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&dq=sailing+yacht+insurance+categories&hl=en|title=RYA Stability & Buoyancy (E-G23)|date=2018-12-20|publisher=Royal Yachting Association|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==== Offshore ====\nOffshore cruising sailboats typically exceed {{Convert|45|ft|m|abbr=}} length overall.<ref name=\":4\" /> The Royal Yachting Association has two design categories for yachts used in this context: \"A\" yachts are fit for conditions that <u>exceed</u> wind force 8\u2014{{Convert|40|kn|m/s|abbr=}}\u2014and {{Convert|4|m|ft|abbr=|order=flip|adj=on}} wave heights. \"B\" yachts are fit for <u>up to</u> that threshold.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n=== Design ===\nCatamarans offer tradeoffs as cruising sailboats, compared with [[Monohull|monohulls]]. Their advantages include greater: stability, speed, living space, and shallower draft. Their drawbacks include: greater expenses, greater [[windage]], more difficult tacking under sail, less load capacity, and more maneuvering room required because of their broad beam. They come with a variety of sleeping accommodations and bridge-deck configurations. <ref>{{Cite book|last=Tarjan, Gregor.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/233534126|title=Catamarans : the complete guide for cruising sailors|date=2008|publisher=International Marine|isbn=978-0-07-159622-0|location=Camden, Me.|oclc=233534126}}</ref>\n\n=== Construction ===\n\n=== Rigs ===\n\n=== Gear ===\n\n=== Accommodations ===\n\n=== Systems ===\n\n==Racing==\n{{Under construction|section=Description|placedby=HopsonRoad}}\nWorld Sailing recognizes nine classes of racing yacht:<ref>[http://www.sailing.org/classes/#isaf_sliding_tab_item_classes_index_yacht World Sailing classes of yachts].</ref>\n\n#[[Class40]]\n#[[Farr 30]]\n#[[Farr 40]]\n#[[International Maxi Association]]\n#[[J/111]]\n#[[IMOCA 60]]\n#[[Soto 40]]\n#[[Swan 45]]\n#[[Swan 60]]\n#[[TP 52]]\n#[[X-35 (yacht)|X-35]]\n#[[X-41 (yacht)|X-41]]\n\n==See also==\n{{commonscat-inline|Sailing yachts}}\n*[[Dinghy sailing]]\n*[[International class]]\n*[[List of large sailing yachts]]\n*[[Skiff|Sailing skiff]]\n{{International Sailing Federation Classes}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n[[Category:Sailing yachts]]\n", "name_user": "HopsonRoad", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCategories:Bullets suffice.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sailing_yacht"}
{"title_page": "Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n| name = Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology\n| image = RUET logo.svg\n| caption = Logo of the Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology\n| native_name = \u09b0\u09be\u099c\u09b6\u09be\u09b9\u09c0 \u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u0995\u09cc\u09b6\u09b2 \u0993 \u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09af\u09c1\u0995\u09cd\u09a4\u09bf \u09ac\u09bf\u09b6\u09cd\u09ac\u09ac\u09bf\u09a6\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09b2\u09af\u09bc (''R\u0101j\u015b\u0101h\u012b Prakau\u015bal \u014d Prayukti Bi\u015bbabidy\u0101lay.'')\n| motto = \u0990\u09b6\u09c0 \u099c\u09cd\u09af\u09cb\u09a4\u09bf\u0987 \u0986\u09ae\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b0 \u09aa\u09a5 \u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a6\u09b0\u09cd\u09b6\u0995 (''ai\u015b\u012b jy\u014dtii \u0101m\u0101d\u0113ra patha pradar\u015baka'')\n| motto_lang = bn\n| mottoeng = ''Heaven's Light is Our Guide''\n| established = {{start date|1964}}\n| type = [[Public university|Public]] [[Engineering education|engineering university]]\n| budget = [[\u09f3]] 1.14 billion (2018) <br /> ([[$]] 13.5 million)<ref name=\"ugc\">{{cite web|url=http://ugc.portal.gov.bd/sites/default/files/files/ugc.portal.gov.bd/publications/bb42893b_ece2_4084_a486_be3e2dfd5aa1/UGC_RSP.zip|title=UGC Publications|publisher=[[University Grants Commission (Bangladesh)]]|archive-url=http://www.ugc.gov.bd/site/view/publications/-|archive-date=2019-03-12 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| chancellor = [[President of Bangladesh]]\n| vice_chancellor = Md. Rafiqul Islam Sheikh<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/teacher/EEE/ris86131|title=Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology - RUET|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2018-08-28}}</ref>\n| academic_staff = 254<ref name=\"faculty\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ugc.gov.bd/reports/Part%202.7.doc |title=UGC Annual Report 2008 |website=University Grants Commission |accessdate=2011-01-17}}</ref>\n| administrative_staff = 389\n| students = 5954\n| undergrad = 5225\n| postgrad = 553\n| doctoral = 176\n| city = [[Rajshahi]]\n| country = {{flagicon|BGD}}  [[Bangladesh]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|24.3635|88.6280|region:BD_type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n| campus = [[urban area|Urban]], 152 acres (0.61&nbsp;km\u00b2)\n| website = {{URL|www.ruet.ac.bd}}\n| address = 6204 Rajshahi - Dhaka Hwy, Rajshahi\n| former_names = 1964: Rajshahi Engineering College (REC)<br />1986: Bangladesh Institute of Technology (BIT), Rajshahi\n| language = English\n}}\n'''Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology''', commonly known as '''RUET (\u09b0\u09c1\u09af\u09bc\u09c7\u099f),''' is one of the leading [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] granting [[Public university|public]] [[research]] [[List of universities in Bangladesh|universities in Bangladesh]]. It is one of the most prestigious public universities in the country that specialises in the field of [[engineering]]. Just like the other public engineering universities, the admission battle of RUET is considered to be the toughest one in the country as a student has to go through the selection process based in their grades and after getting selected, written examination .<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nRUET was founded in 1964 as Rajshahi Engineering College with a limited number of students. It was then changed to Bangladesh Institute of Technology (BIT) in 1986 and was finally renamed Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology (RUET) in 2003 when it gained a university status.\n\nAt present, more than 3500 students are pursuing their higher study in this green campus including under-graduate and post-graduate with over 250 prominent faculty members in diverse field of expertise. The medium of instruction and necessary assessment of this university is English.<ref name=\"StarCampus\">{{cite news |last=Kaioum |first=Md.Mamun Abdul |date=2009-11-01 |title=RUET: Glorious 45 Years of Engineering Excellence |url=http://archive.thedailystar.net/campus/2009/11/01/feature_ruet.htm |work=Star Campus |publisher=The Daily Star |access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nBefore the [[History of bangladesh|independence of Bangladesh]], the then [[Government of Pakistan]], to meet the increasing demand of professional engineers for the national development, established Rajshahi Engineering College in 1964 as a faculty of engineering under the [[University of Rajshahi]]. It was the second engineering college established in the then [[East Pakistan]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/articles/History/5|title=Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology - RUET|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2016-12-02}}</ref>\n\nRajshahi Engineering College ( was commonly known as REC) started its journey with only three departments: Mechanical Engineering, Electrical & Electronic Engineering and Civil Engineering, offering bachelor's degree programs only. It accepted its first class of 120 students in the academic session of 1964/65 and the second class of like number in the academic session of 1965/66. The teaching faculty consisted of 19 faculty members at that time.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://unesdoc.unesco.org/images/0003/000300/030035EB.pdf|title=Higher Engineering Education in East Pakistan|last=|first=|publisher=UNESCO|year=1966|isbn=|location=Paris|pages=41\u201342|quote=}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[History of Bangladesh|independence of Bangladesh]] (1971), the administration of the college was controlled by the [[Ministry of Education (Bangladesh)|Ministry of Education of Bangladesh]] and academic curriculum was controlled by [[University of Rajshahi]]. However, the infrastructural development and maintenance was taken care of by the Public Works Department of [[Government of Bangladesh]]. To remove these kinds of aforesaid problems several committees and commissions were formed since 1973. On the recommendation of these committees and commissions, in 1986, Rajshahi Engineering College was converted to an institute and was named Bangladesh Institute of Technology (BIT), Rajshahi to enhance the technical education.<ref>{{cite news |title=KUET, RUET, DUET celebrate founding anniversary |url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/printversion/details/14093 |newspaper=The Independent |location=Dhaka |date=2015-09-02 |access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref>\n\nIn September, 2003, the institute was upgraded to a university and was named as Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology (RUET) to enhance the technical education and research.<ref>{{cite news |title=RUET celebrates 13th anniversary |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/city/ruet-celebrates-13th-anniversary-1279189 |newspaper=The Daily Star |date=2016-09-02 |access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref> From that time, the university is financed by the Government through the [[University Grants Commission (Bangladesh)|University Grants Commission (UGC) of Bangladesh]]. The university is an autonomous statutory organisation of the Government of Bangladesh functioning within the \"Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology: Act 2003\".\n\n==Campus==\nRUET is situated in the northern part of Bangladesh, in the city of [[Rajshahi]]\u2014 the educational center of [[North Bengal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/articles/Campus%20Details/219|title=Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology - RUET|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2016-12-02}}</ref> The RUET campus has been described as representing a \"spectacular harmony of architecture and natural beauty\".<ref name=\"StarCampus\" />\n\nThe distinguishable seasons in Bangladesh are summer and winter. In summer season (May\u2013October) temperature of Rajshahi is hot and typically 25-40 degree Celsius and sometimes humid. In winter season (November\u2013April) temperature is moderate typically 8-20 degree Celsius.\n\n==Faculties and departments==\nRUET has currently eighteen departments under four faculties. The university has taken to plan open more departments which was under process.\n\n===Faculty of Mechanical Engineering===\n* Department of [[Industrial and production engineering|Industrial & Production Engineering (IPE)]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/faculties#faculty_ME|title=Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology - RUET|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2016-12-02}}</ref>\n* Department of [[Ceramic engineering|Glass & Ceramic Engineering (GCE)]]\n* Department of [[Mechatronics|Mechatronics Engineering (MTE)]]\n* Department of [[Mechanical engineering|Mechanical Engineering (ME)]]\n* Department of [[Materials Science & Engineering|Material Science & Engineering (MSE)]]<ref>{{cite news |title=RUET launches two departments |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/city/ruet-starts-2-departments-session-1278208 |newspaper=The Daily Star |date=2016-08-31 |access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref>\n* Department of [[Process engineering|Chemical & Food Process Engineering (CFPE)]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.samakal.net/2016/01/05/2215|title=RUET starts a new department|access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref>\n\n===Faculty of Civil Engineering===\n* Department of [[Civil engineering|Civil Engineering (CE)]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/faculties#faculty_CE|title=Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology - RUET|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2016-12-02}}</ref>\n* Department of [[Urban planning|Urban & Regional Planning (URP)]]\n* Department of [[Architecture|Architecture (Arch.)]]\n* Department of [[Geotechnical & Geo-Environmental Engineering | Geotechnical & Geo-Environmental Engineering (GGE)]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/faculties#faculty_CE|title=Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology - RUET|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2016-12-02}}</ref>\n* Department of [[Construction management|Building Engineering & Construction Management (BECM)]]\n<ref>{{cite news |title=RUET to launch two more departments|url=http://www.thefinancialexpress-bd.com/2016/08/31/44166/RUET-to-launch-two-more-deptts |newspaper=The Financial Express |location=Dhaka |date=2016-08-31 |access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref>\n\n===Faculty of Electrical & Computer Engineering===\n* Department of [[Computer science|Computer Science & Engineering (CSE)]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/faculties#faculty_ECE|title=Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology - RUET|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2016-12-02}}</ref>\n* Department of [[Electrical engineering|Electrical & Electronic Engineering (EEE)]]\n* Department of [[Telecommunications engineering|Electronics & Telecommunication Engineering (ETE)]]\n* Department of [[Computer engineering|Electrical & Computer Engineering(ECE)]]\n* Department of [[Bio-Medical Engineering |Bio-Medical Engineering (BME)]] \n* Department of [[Computer Science & Information Engineering |Computer Science & Information Engineering (CSIE)]]\n\n===Faculty of Applied Science and Engineering===\n* Department of [[Chemistry|Chemistry (Chem)]]\n* Department of [[Mathematics|Mathematics (Math)]]\n* Department of [[Physics|Physics (Phy)]]\n* Department of [[Humanities|Humanities (Hum)]]\n\n== Academics ==\n\n=== Research ===\n\n==== Research projects ====\nRUET won a total of three projects (excluding BdREN project) for improving postgraduate research facilities and producing quality postgraduates from the \"Higher Education Quality Enhancement Project (HEQEP)\" funded by the [[World Bank]] and the Government of Bangladesh during the period of 2014 \u2013 2017. Lists of ongoing research project are as follows:\n# Improvement of research capabilities of Mechanical Engineering Department of RUET for producing quality postgraduates and enhancing research outreach.\n# Improving research facilities in Mechanical Engineering Department of RUET for post-graduate studies.\n# Development of teaching learning facilities for undergraduate & graduate program in Mechanical Engineering Department of RUET<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/articles/Research%20Project/232|title=Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology - RUET|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2016-12-03}}</ref>\n\n==== Research institutes ====\nRUET has currently following research institutes:\n* Institute of [[Information and Communication Technology | Information and Communication Technology (IICT)]]\n* Institute of [[Energy and Environmental Studies | Energy and Environmental Studies (IEES)]]\n* Institute of [[ Natural Hazard & Disaster Management | Natural Hazard & Disaster Management (INHDM)]]\nRUET has already taken plan to open more research institutes to enhance the technical education and research activities.\n\n==== Research and extension unit ====\nThe research and outreach program of RUET is conducted by the research and extension unit. The main responsibilities of this unit is management of research, innovation, research publications, research planning, implementation, research related activities and research related communication with public and private sectors in nation and international level.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/articles/Research%20and%20Extension%20Unit/236|title=Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology - RUET|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2016-12-03}}</ref>\n\n==== International collaboration ====\nRUET has collaborative agreements with foreign institute and will extend further to enhance the research work, technical knowledge and skills. The collaborative areas covered are joint research activities, joint hosting of seminars, conferences and symposia, exchange of students (both [[Undergraduate education|UG]] and [[Postgraduate education|PG]]), exchange of faculty members, exchange of academic materials, publications and information etc. At present, the collaboration of RUET exists with the following ones. \n# [[Kitami Institute of Technology|Kitami Institute of Technology (KIT)]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kitami-it.ac.jp/about/interchange-en/|title=Kitami Institute of Technology}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/articles/International%20Collaboration/234|title=Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology - RUET|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2016-12-09}}</ref>\n# [[University of the Ryukyus]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://w3.u-ryukyu.ac.jp/gakusaibu/kokusai/english-partner-universities/?lang=en|title=University of the Ryukyus}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n# [[Saitama University]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://me.ruet.ac.bd/research-collaboration|title=Research Collaboration - Department of Mechanical Engineering, RUET|last=ClrsHQ|website=me.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2016-12-09}}</ref>\n\n==== International conferences ====\nFor the last few years, RUET has been organising national and international [[Academic conference|conferences]] in its campus to enhance the research capabilities of its students and faculties. Among the conferences organised by RUET, the following ones are notable.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/|title=Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology - RUET|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2016-12-03}}</ref>\n* International Conference on Mechanical, Industrial and Materials Engineering (ICMIME): Organised biennially by the faculty of Mechanical Engineering<ref>{{cite news |title=International Mechanical Engineering Conference ends at RUET |url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/printversion/details/26627 |newspaper=The Independent |location=Dhaka |agency=BSS |date=2015-12-14 |access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref>\n* International Conference on Electrical, Computer and Telecommunication Engineering (ICECTE): Organised biennially by the faculty of Electrical and Computer Engineering\n* International Conference on Planning, Architecture and Civil Engineering (ICPACE):  Organised biennially by the faculty of Civil Engineering\n* International Conference on Electrical and Electronic Engineering (ICEEE): Organised biennially by the department of Electrical and Electronic Engineering<ref>{{cite web |title=Three-day ICEEE confce concludes at RUET|url=http://print.thefinancialexpress-bd.com/2015/11/07/115947 |newspaper=The Financial Express |location=Dhaka |date=2015-11-07 |access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref>\n* International Conference on Computer & Information Engineering (ICCIE): Organised biennially by the department of Computer Science and Engineering<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thebangladeshtoday.com/2015/11/conference-on-computer-and-information-engineering-begins-at-ruet/|title=Conference on Computer and Information Engineering begins at RUET - The Bangladesh Today|date=2015-11-26|newspaper=The Bangladesh Today|language=en-US|access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref>\n\n=== Admission ===\nGetting into the major engineering university like [[RUET]], it appears to be the toughest public university admission test battle to the aspiring candidates. RUET has a very selective approach when it comes to admitting a certain number of students into various disciplines of engineering each year.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/shout/cover-story/public-university-admission-battle-122224|title=Public University Admission Battle|last=|first=|date=|work=The Daily Star|access-date=30 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Undergraduate====\nThe undergraduate admissions process begins after all education boards of the country declare the results of the Higher Secondary Certificate (HSC) examinations. After initial assortment according to HSC result, a certain number of eligible candidates are shortlisted for an elaborate written test.<ref name=\":0\" /> Usually application for admission start from September of each year, and an admission test is usually held in October or November as per decision of the admission committee.{{citation needed|date=January 2017}} A total of 875 students were admitted in 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newagebd.net/article/1370/ruet-intake-test-on-26-october|title=RUET intake test on 26 October|date=2016-10-24|newspaper=New Age|location=Dhaka|access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref>\n\n====Post-graduate====\nAdmission notices for the post-graduate program usually circulate twice a year, in April and October. The notice is advertised on the university website. The list of valid candidates is published on the university website upon completion of the preliminary process and call for viva.{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\n==Facilities==\n\n=== Laboratories ===\nMost of the newly established departments of the RUET don't have enough laboratory facilities. But the older ones have enough laboratory facilities not only for academic research but also for consultancy services.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Amin |first=Boni |date=2015-09-17 |title=How to ensure the qualities of building construction materials |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/science-arts-construction-materials/how-ensure-the-qualities-building-construction-materials-144673 |newspaper=The Daily Star |access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref> RUET is taking steps for establishing laboratory facilities for the newly established departments and for enhancing laboratory facilities for the older ones.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ugc.gov.bd/en/home/recentnews/469|title=University Grants Commission|last=humans.txt|website=www.ugc.gov.bd|access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref>\n\n==== ''Faculty of Civil Engineering'' ====\n\n===== Department of Civil Engineering =====\n* Soil Mechanics Lab\n* Strength of Materials Lab\n* Fluid Lab\n* Environment Lab\n* Public Health Lab\n* Transportation Lab\n* Concrete Lab\n\n===== Department of Urban & Regional Planning =====\n* GIS Laboratory\n* Cartography Laboratory<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/articles/Laboratories/211|title=Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology - RUET|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2016-12-03}}</ref>\n\n==== ''Faculty of Mechanical Engineering'' ====\n\n===== Department of Mechanical Engineering =====\n* Thermal Engineering Lab (Heat Engine Lab)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/articles/List%20of%20Laboratories/93|title=Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology - RUET|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2016-12-03}}</ref>\n* Fluid Mechanics and Energy Lab\n* Applied Mechanics and Machine Design Lab\n* Material Science and Metallurgy Lab\n* Metrology Lab\n* Wood Shop\n* Machine Shop\n* Foundry Shop\n* Boiler Shop\n* Fitting Shop\n* Welding & Sheet Metal Shop\n* Computer Lab\n\n===== Department of Glass and Ceramic Engineering =====\n* Ceramic Forming Lab\n* Micro-structure Lab\n* Ceramic Testing Lab<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/articles/Laboratories/142|title=Department of Glass and Ceramic Engineering Laboratories, RUET|last=|first=|date=|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|publisher=|access-date=2016-12-03}}</ref>\n\n==== ''Faculty Of Electrical and Computer Engineering'' ====\n\n===== Department of Electrical and Electronic Engineering =====\n* Electrical Machine LAB<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/articles/Laboratories/158|title=Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology - RUET|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2016-12-03}}</ref>\n* Electronics and Power Electronics Lab\n* Electrical Circuit and Measurement Lab\n* Computer Lab(1)\n* Telecommunications and Microwave Lab\n* Photovoltaic and Nanotechnology Lab\n*Computer Lab(2)\n*Power Electronics & Green Energy lab.\n* High Voltage Lab\n\n===== Department of Computer Science and Engineering =====\n* Software Lab<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/articles/Laboratories%20in%20Dept.%20of%20CSE/78|title=Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology - RUET|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2016-12-03}}</ref>\n* Network Lab\n* Operating System Lab\n* Hardware Lab\n* ACL Lab\n* Game and Android Development Lab\n\n===== Department of Electronics and Telecommunication Engineering =====\n* Communication Laboratory<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/articles/Laboratories/195|title=Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology - RUET|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2016-12-03}}</ref>\n* Antenna and Propagation Laboratory\n* Photonics Laboratory\n* Digital Signal Processing Laboratory\n* Microelectronics Laboratory\n\n==== Other laboratories ====\n* Physics Lab<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/articles/Laboratories/154|title=Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology - RUET|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2016-12-03}}</ref>\n* Chemistry Lab\n\n=== Further development ===\nIn February, 2017, [[Bangladesh Planning Commission#Executive Committee of the National Economic Council .28ECNEC.29|Executive Committee of National Economic Council (ECNEC)]] has approved 3.40 billion Taka to implement a mega project for the RUET, aiming to well decorate and development the whole campus and its education and research. The ECNEC approved the project in the name of \"Further Development Project of RUET\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thefinancialexpress-bd.com/2017/02/15/61948/Tk-3.40m-mega-project-for-RUET-development|title=Tk 3.40m mega-project for RUET development|newspaper=The Financial Express|access-date=2 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Student life==\n\n=== Accommodation ===\nStudent dormitories (called halls) are important features in campus life. There are seven residential halls. One of them, namely Deshratna Sheikh Hasina Hall, is for female students and the remaining ones are for male students. The administrative head of a hall is its provost, usually chosen from the more senior teachers. The halls are mostly named after national heroes and leaders. These are listed below with their capacities:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/articles/Accommodation/19|title=Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology - RUET|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2016-12-03}}</ref> \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name of the halls\n! Capacity\n|-\n|Shahid Shahidul Islam Hall\n|225\n|-\n|Shahid Abdul Hamid Hall\n|225\n|-\n|Tin Shed Hall (extension of Shahid Sahidul Islam Hall)\n|100\n|-\n|Deshratna Sheikh Hasina Hall\n|120\n|-\n|Shahid President Ziaur Rahman Hall\n|500\n|-\n|Bangabondhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Hall\n|250\n|-\n|Shahid Lieutenant Salim hall\n|350\n|}\n\n===Organisations and clubs===\nStudents of RUET are involved in different organisations and clubs of the university. Members of these organisations and clubs organise different national programs at RUET.<ref>{{cite news |title=Campus corner |url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/printversion/details/41281 |newspaper=The Independent |location=Dhaka |date=2016-04-21 |access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref> They also participate in different national and international competitions and shows indomitable performances.<ref>{{cite news |title=RUET clinches championship in eco-run-2015 contest |url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/printversion/details/27475 |newspaper=The Independent |location=Dhaka |agency=BSS |date=2015-12-21 |access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref> Some of the leading organisations and clubs of RUET are mentioned here. \n* IEEE RUET Student Branch\n* Robotic Society of RUET (RSR)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rsr-ruet.org/|title=www.rsr-ruet.org {{!}} Robotic Society of RUET|website=www.rsr-ruet.org|access-date=2016-12-06}}</ref>\n* Society of Automotive Engineers-RUET (SAER)\n* Civil Engineering Society of RUET<ref>{{cite news |title=Campus corner |url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/printversion/details/32316 |newspaper=The Independent |location=Dhaka |date=2016-02-01 |access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref>\n* RUET Debating Club (RUET DC)\n* RUET Career Forum (RCF)<ref>{{cite news |title=Two-day job fair starts at Ruet |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/city/two-day-job-fair-starts-ruet-199129 |newspaper=The Daily Star |date=2016-01-09 |access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref>\n* Telecommunication Club\n* RUET Analytical Programming Lab (RAPL)\n* Astronomy and Science Society of RUET ( ASSR )\n* \u0985\u09a8\u09c1\u09b0\u09a3\u09a8: The cultural Club of RUET\n* \u09b8\u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09c1\u09aa\u09be\u09a4\u09bf\u0995 : A voluntary organisation of RUET\n* Photographic Society of RUET (PSR) (Zinnur Rahman is the media secretary of PSR Committee since 2019-2020)\n* RUET Cricket Club\n* RUET Football Club (RUET FC)\n* Society of Computer Aided Designer, RUET (SCADR)\n* RUET Earthquake Society\n* RUET AutoCad Club\n* Tennis Club RUET \n* Team Crack Platoon\n* RUET Fitness Club\n* \u09a8\u09bf\u09b0\u09be\u09aa\u09a6 \u09b0\u0995\u09cd\u09a4\u09c7\u09b0 \u09ac\u09a8\u09cd\u09a7\u09a8(\u09a8\u09bf\u09b0\u09ac) : A voluntary blood donating organisation of RUET\n* Machine Learning Group Of RUET\n* RUET English Language Club (RELC)\n* RUET Firefox Club\n* Cube Club of RUET\n* RUET Film Club\n* Mathematical Society of RUET\n* RUET Tourist Club\n* RUET HAWKS (RUET Basketball Club)\n* RUET Chess Club\n* Innovation Society of RUET (ISR)\n\n=== Others ===\nThe athletic club of the university provides multi-purpose sports facilities to the students to acquire physical fitness indispensable for a healthy mind and body. The university maintains a beautiful playground for football, cricket, badminton, volleyball, long tennis, basketball, etc. Indoor facilities are also available in the physical education building close to the playground.\n\nRUET has a library, a central computer center, an auditorium, a canteen, a cafeteria, a medical center, a postal service and a banking service. RUET also has its own regular bus service almost everywhere in the Rajshahi city for the convenience of student transportation. Students these are residing in the city outside the campus can take this transport service to reached the campus due time.\n\n==Awards==\n* RUET won the IEEE Photonics GSF Award, USA in October 2009\n* RUET won the Marubun Research Promotion Award, Japan in March 2009\n\n==Education cost==\nYearly academic cost is $40 (2800 Taka) (approx) in all departments. Admission cost is $213 (18,000Taka) (approx) including academic cost (admission, session, registration and student fees), medical costs, library, sports, convocation (3500 Taka) and others expenditure and for one time in four years bachelor's degree.<ref name=\"ksdroy\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/articles/Study%20Expenditure/228 |title=RUET Study Expenditure |website=RUET  |accessdate=2015-01-24}}</ref>\n\n== Photos ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Shahid Zia Hall.jpg|Shahid Zia Hall\nFile:Bongobondhu Hall Ruet.jpg|Bangabandhu Hall\nFile:Ladies Hall.jpg|Ladies Hall\n</gallery>\n{{commons category|Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Universities in Bangladesh]]\n* [[Bangladesh University of Engineering and Technology|BUET]]\n* [[Chittagong University of Engineering & Technology|CUET]]\n* [[Khulna University of Engineering & Technology|KUET]]\n* [[University Grants Commission (Bangladesh)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n01.[http://m.banglatribune.com/national/news/348953/%E0%A6%B0%E0%A7%81%E0%A7%9F%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%9F%E0%A7%87-%E0%A6%A8%E0%A6%A4%E0%A7%81%E0%A6%A8-%E0%A6%AD%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%B8%E0%A6%BF-%E0%A6%A1.-%E0%A6%AE%E0%A7%8B.-%E0%A6%B0%E0%A6%AB%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%95%E0%A7%81%E0%A6%B2-%E0%A6%87%E0%A6%B8%E0%A6%B2%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%AE-%E0%A6%B6%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%96  \u09b0\u09c1\u09af\u09bc\u09c7\u099f\u09c7\u09b0 \u09a8\u09a4\u09c1\u09a8 \u09ad\u09bf\u09b8\u09bf \u09a1. \u09ae\u09cb. \u09b0\u09ab\u09bf\u0995\u09c1\u09b2 \u0987\u09b8\u09b2\u09be\u09ae \u09b6\u09c7\u0996 ]\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology}}\n* [http://www.ruet.ac.bd Official website of RUET]\n* [http://www.rsr-ruet.org Website of Robotic Society of RUET]\n* [http://www.ipetalks.com Website of IPE Department]\n\n{{Public Universities of Bangladesh}}\n{{Public Engineering Universities of Bangladesh}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rajshahi University Of Engineering and Technology}}\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1964]]\n[[Category:1964 establishments in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Technological institutes of Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Public engineering universities of Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Engineering universities and colleges in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Education in Rajshahi]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox university\n| name = Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology\n| image = RUET logo.svg\n| caption = Logo of the Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology\n| native_name = \u09b0\u09be\u099c\u09b6\u09be\u09b9\u09c0 \u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u0995\u09cc\u09b6\u09b2 \u0993 \u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09af\u09c1\u0995\u09cd\u09a4\u09bf \u09ac\u09bf\u09b6\u09cd\u09ac\u09ac\u09bf\u09a6\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09b2\u09af\u09bc (''R\u0101j\u015b\u0101h\u012b Prakau\u015bal \u014d Prayukti Bi\u015bbabidy\u0101lay.'')\n| motto = \u0990\u09b6\u09c0 \u099c\u09cd\u09af\u09cb\u09a4\u09bf\u0987 \u0986\u09ae\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b0 \u09aa\u09a5 \u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a6\u09b0\u09cd\u09b6\u0995 (''ai\u015b\u012b jy\u014dtii \u0101m\u0101d\u0113ra patha pradar\u015baka'')\n| motto_lang = bn\n| mottoeng = ''Heaven's Light is Our Guide''\n| established = {{start date|1964}}\n| type = [[Public university|Public]] [[Engineering education|engineering university]]\n| budget = [[\u09f3]] 1.14 billion (2018) <br /> ([[$]] 13.5 million)<ref name=\"ugc\">{{cite web|url=http://ugc.portal.gov.bd/sites/default/files/files/ugc.portal.gov.bd/publications/bb42893b_ece2_4084_a486_be3e2dfd5aa1/UGC_RSP.zip|title=UGC Publications|publisher=[[University Grants Commission (Bangladesh)]]|archive-url=http://www.ugc.gov.bd/site/view/publications/-|archive-date=2019-03-12 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| chancellor = [[President of Bangladesh]]\n| vice_chancellor = Md. Rafiqul Islam Sheikh<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/teacher/EEE/ris86131|title=Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology - RUET|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2018-08-28}}</ref>\n| academic_staff = 254<ref name=\"faculty\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ugc.gov.bd/reports/Part%202.7.doc |title=UGC Annual Report 2008 |website=University Grants Commission |accessdate=2011-01-17}}</ref>\n| administrative_staff = 389\n| students = 5954\n| undergrad = 5225\n| postgrad = 553\n| doctoral = 176\n| city = [[Rajshahi]]\n| country = {{flagicon|BGD}}  [[Bangladesh]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|24.3635|88.6280|region:BD_type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n| campus = [[urban area|Urban]], 152 acres (0.61&nbsp;km\u00b2)\n| website = {{URL|www.ruet.ac.bd}}\n| former_names = 1964: Rajshahi Engineering College (REC)<br />1986: Bangladesh Institute of Technology (BIT), Rajshahi\n| language = English\n}}\n'''Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology''', commonly known as '''RUET (\u09b0\u09c1\u09af\u09bc\u09c7\u099f),''' is one of the leading [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] granting [[Public university|public]] [[research]] [[List of universities in Bangladesh|universities in Bangladesh]]. It is one of the most prestigious public universities in the country that specialises in the field of [[engineering]]. Just like the other public engineering universities, the admission battle of RUET is considered to be the toughest one in the country as a student has to go through the selection process based in their grades and after getting selected, written examination .<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nRUET was founded in 1964 as Rajshahi Engineering College with a limited number of students. It was then changed to Bangladesh Institute of Technology (BIT) in 1986 and was finally renamed Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology (RUET) in 2003 when it gained a university status.\n\nAt present, more than 3500 students are pursuing their higher study in this green campus including under-graduate and post-graduate with over 250 prominent faculty members in diverse field of expertise. The medium of instruction and necessary assessment of this university is English.<ref name=\"StarCampus\">{{cite news |last=Kaioum |first=Md.Mamun Abdul |date=2009-11-01 |title=RUET: Glorious 45 Years of Engineering Excellence |url=http://archive.thedailystar.net/campus/2009/11/01/feature_ruet.htm |work=Star Campus |publisher=The Daily Star |access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nBefore the [[History of bangladesh|independence of Bangladesh]], the then [[Government of Pakistan]], to meet the increasing demand of professional engineers for the national development, established Rajshahi Engineering College in 1964 as a faculty of engineering under the [[University of Rajshahi]]. It was the second engineering college established in the then [[East Pakistan]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/articles/History/5|title=Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology - RUET|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2016-12-02}}</ref>\n\nRajshahi Engineering College ( was commonly known as REC) started its journey with only three departments: Mechanical Engineering, Electrical & Electronic Engineering and Civil Engineering, offering bachelor's degree programs only. It accepted its first class of 120 students in the academic session of 1964/65 and the second class of like number in the academic session of 1965/66. The teaching faculty consisted of 19 faculty members at that time.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://unesdoc.unesco.org/images/0003/000300/030035EB.pdf|title=Higher Engineering Education in East Pakistan|last=|first=|publisher=UNESCO|year=1966|isbn=|location=Paris|pages=41\u201342|quote=}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[History of Bangladesh|independence of Bangladesh]] (1971), the administration of the college was controlled by the [[Ministry of Education (Bangladesh)|Ministry of Education of Bangladesh]] and academic curriculum was controlled by [[University of Rajshahi]]. However, the infrastructural development and maintenance was taken care of by the Public Works Department of [[Government of Bangladesh]]. To remove these kinds of aforesaid problems several committees and commissions were formed since 1973. On the recommendation of these committees and commissions, in 1986, Rajshahi Engineering College was converted to an institute and was named Bangladesh Institute of Technology (BIT), Rajshahi to enhance the technical education.<ref>{{cite news |title=KUET, RUET, DUET celebrate founding anniversary |url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/printversion/details/14093 |newspaper=The Independent |location=Dhaka |date=2015-09-02 |access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref>\n\nIn September, 2003, the institute was upgraded to a university and was named as Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology (RUET) to enhance the technical education and research.<ref>{{cite news |title=RUET celebrates 13th anniversary |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/city/ruet-celebrates-13th-anniversary-1279189 |newspaper=The Daily Star |date=2016-09-02 |access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref> From that time, the university is financed by the Government through the [[University Grants Commission (Bangladesh)|University Grants Commission (UGC) of Bangladesh]]. The university is an autonomous statutory organisation of the Government of Bangladesh functioning within the \"Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology: Act 2003\".\n\n==Campus==\nRUET is situated in the northern part of Bangladesh, in the city of [[Rajshahi]]\u2014 the educational center of [[North Bengal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/articles/Campus%20Details/219|title=Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology - RUET|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2016-12-02}}</ref> The RUET campus has been described as representing a \"spectacular harmony of architecture and natural beauty\".<ref name=\"StarCampus\" />\n\nThe distinguishable seasons in Bangladesh are summer and winter. In summer season (May\u2013October) temperature of Rajshahi is hot and typically 25-40 degree Celsius and sometimes humid. In winter season (November\u2013April) temperature is moderate typically 8-20 degree Celsius.\n\n==Faculties and departments==\nRUET has currently eighteen departments under four faculties. The university has taken to plan open more departments which was under process.\n\n===Faculty of Mechanical Engineering===\n* Department of [[Industrial and production engineering|Industrial & Production Engineering (IPE)]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/faculties#faculty_ME|title=Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology - RUET|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2016-12-02}}</ref>\n* Department of [[Ceramic engineering|Glass & Ceramic Engineering (GCE)]]\n* Department of [[Mechatronics|Mechatronics Engineering (MTE)]]\n* Department of [[Mechanical engineering|Mechanical Engineering (ME)]]\n* Department of [[Materials Science & Engineering|Material Science & Engineering (MSE)]]<ref>{{cite news |title=RUET launches two departments |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/city/ruet-starts-2-departments-session-1278208 |newspaper=The Daily Star |date=2016-08-31 |access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref>\n* Department of [[Process engineering|Chemical & Food Process Engineering (CFPE)]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.samakal.net/2016/01/05/2215|title=RUET starts a new department|access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref>\n\n===Faculty of Civil Engineering===\n* Department of [[Civil engineering|Civil Engineering (CE)]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/faculties#faculty_CE|title=Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology - RUET|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2016-12-02}}</ref>\n* Department of [[Urban planning|Urban & Regional Planning (URP)]]\n* Department of [[Architecture|Architecture (Arch.)]]\n* Department of [[Geotechnical & Geo-Environmental Engineering | Geotechnical & Geo-Environmental Engineering (GGE)]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/faculties#faculty_CE|title=Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology - RUET|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2016-12-02}}</ref>\n* Department of [[Construction management|Building Engineering & Construction Management (BECM)]]\n<ref>{{cite news |title=RUET to launch two more departments|url=http://www.thefinancialexpress-bd.com/2016/08/31/44166/RUET-to-launch-two-more-deptts |newspaper=The Financial Express |location=Dhaka |date=2016-08-31 |access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref>\n\n===Faculty of Electrical & Computer Engineering===\n* Department of [[Computer science|Computer Science & Engineering (CSE)]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/faculties#faculty_ECE|title=Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology - RUET|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2016-12-02}}</ref>\n* Department of [[Electrical engineering|Electrical & Electronic Engineering (EEE)]]\n* Department of [[Telecommunications engineering|Electronics & Telecommunication Engineering (ETE)]]\n* Department of [[Computer engineering|Electrical & Computer Engineering(ECE)]]\n* Department of [[Bio-Medical Engineering |Bio-Medical Engineering (BME)]] \n* Department of [[Computer Science & Information Engineering |Computer Science & Information Engineering (CSIE)]]\n\n===Faculty of Applied Science and Engineering===\n* Department of [[Chemistry|Chemistry (Chem)]]\n* Department of [[Mathematics|Mathematics (Math)]]\n* Department of [[Physics|Physics (Phy)]]\n* Department of [[Humanities|Humanities (Hum)]]\n\n== Academics ==\n\n=== Research ===\n\n==== Research projects ====\nRUET won a total of three projects (excluding BdREN project) for improving postgraduate research facilities and producing quality postgraduates from the \"Higher Education Quality Enhancement Project (HEQEP)\" funded by the [[World Bank]] and the Government of Bangladesh during the period of 2014 \u2013 2017. Lists of ongoing research project are as follows:\n# Improvement of research capabilities of Mechanical Engineering Department of RUET for producing quality postgraduates and enhancing research outreach.\n# Improving research facilities in Mechanical Engineering Department of RUET for post-graduate studies.\n# Development of teaching learning facilities for undergraduate & graduate program in Mechanical Engineering Department of RUET<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/articles/Research%20Project/232|title=Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology - RUET|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2016-12-03}}</ref>\n\n==== Research institutes ====\nRUET has currently following research institutes:\n* Institute of [[Information and Communication Technology | Information and Communication Technology (IICT)]]\n* Institute of [[Energy and Environmental Studies | Energy and Environmental Studies (IEES)]]\n* Institute of [[ Natural Hazard & Disaster Management | Natural Hazard & Disaster Management (INHDM)]]\nRUET has already taken plan to open more research institutes to enhance the technical education and research activities.\n\n==== Research and extension unit ====\nThe research and outreach program of RUET is conducted by the research and extension unit. The main responsibilities of this unit is management of research, innovation, research publications, research planning, implementation, research related activities and research related communication with public and private sectors in nation and international level.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/articles/Research%20and%20Extension%20Unit/236|title=Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology - RUET|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2016-12-03}}</ref>\n\n==== International collaboration ====\nRUET has collaborative agreements with foreign institute and will extend further to enhance the research work, technical knowledge and skills. The collaborative areas covered are joint research activities, joint hosting of seminars, conferences and symposia, exchange of students (both [[Undergraduate education|UG]] and [[Postgraduate education|PG]]), exchange of faculty members, exchange of academic materials, publications and information etc. At present, the collaboration of RUET exists with the following ones. \n# [[Kitami Institute of Technology|Kitami Institute of Technology (KIT)]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kitami-it.ac.jp/about/interchange-en/|title=Kitami Institute of Technology}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/articles/International%20Collaboration/234|title=Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology - RUET|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2016-12-09}}</ref>\n# [[University of the Ryukyus]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://w3.u-ryukyu.ac.jp/gakusaibu/kokusai/english-partner-universities/?lang=en|title=University of the Ryukyus}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n# [[Saitama University]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://me.ruet.ac.bd/research-collaboration|title=Research Collaboration - Department of Mechanical Engineering, RUET|last=ClrsHQ|website=me.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2016-12-09}}</ref>\n\n==== International conferences ====\nFor the last few years, RUET has been organising national and international [[Academic conference|conferences]] in its campus to enhance the research capabilities of its students and faculties. Among the conferences organised by RUET, the following ones are notable.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/|title=Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology - RUET|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2016-12-03}}</ref>\n* International Conference on Mechanical, Industrial and Materials Engineering (ICMIME): Organised biennially by the faculty of Mechanical Engineering<ref>{{cite news |title=International Mechanical Engineering Conference ends at RUET |url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/printversion/details/26627 |newspaper=The Independent |location=Dhaka |agency=BSS |date=2015-12-14 |access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref>\n* International Conference on Electrical, Computer and Telecommunication Engineering (ICECTE): Organised biennially by the faculty of Electrical and Computer Engineering\n* International Conference on Planning, Architecture and Civil Engineering (ICPACE):  Organised biennially by the faculty of Civil Engineering\n* International Conference on Electrical and Electronic Engineering (ICEEE): Organised biennially by the department of Electrical and Electronic Engineering<ref>{{cite web |title=Three-day ICEEE confce concludes at RUET|url=http://print.thefinancialexpress-bd.com/2015/11/07/115947 |newspaper=The Financial Express |location=Dhaka |date=2015-11-07 |access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref>\n* International Conference on Computer & Information Engineering (ICCIE): Organised biennially by the department of Computer Science and Engineering<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thebangladeshtoday.com/2015/11/conference-on-computer-and-information-engineering-begins-at-ruet/|title=Conference on Computer and Information Engineering begins at RUET - The Bangladesh Today|date=2015-11-26|newspaper=The Bangladesh Today|language=en-US|access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref>\n\n=== Admission ===\nGetting into the major engineering university like [[RUET]], it appears to be the toughest public university admission test battle to the aspiring candidates. RUET has a very selective approach when it comes to admitting a certain number of students into various disciplines of engineering each year.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/shout/cover-story/public-university-admission-battle-122224|title=Public University Admission Battle|last=|first=|date=|work=The Daily Star|access-date=30 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Undergraduate====\nThe undergraduate admissions process begins after all education boards of the country declare the results of the Higher Secondary Certificate (HSC) examinations. After initial assortment according to HSC result, a certain number of eligible candidates are shortlisted for an elaborate written test.<ref name=\":0\" /> Usually application for admission start from September of each year, and an admission test is usually held in October or November as per decision of the admission committee.{{citation needed|date=January 2017}} A total of 875 students were admitted in 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newagebd.net/article/1370/ruet-intake-test-on-26-october|title=RUET intake test on 26 October|date=2016-10-24|newspaper=New Age|location=Dhaka|access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref>\n\n====Post-graduate====\nAdmission notices for the post-graduate program usually circulate twice a year, in April and October. The notice is advertised on the university website. The list of valid candidates is published on the university website upon completion of the preliminary process and call for viva.{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\n==Facilities==\n\n=== Laboratories ===\nMost of the newly established departments of the RUET don't have enough laboratory facilities. But the older ones have enough laboratory facilities not only for academic research but also for consultancy services.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Amin |first=Boni |date=2015-09-17 |title=How to ensure the qualities of building construction materials |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/science-arts-construction-materials/how-ensure-the-qualities-building-construction-materials-144673 |newspaper=The Daily Star |access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref> RUET is taking steps for establishing laboratory facilities for the newly established departments and for enhancing laboratory facilities for the older ones.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ugc.gov.bd/en/home/recentnews/469|title=University Grants Commission|last=humans.txt|website=www.ugc.gov.bd|access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref>\n\n==== ''Faculty of Civil Engineering'' ====\n\n===== Department of Civil Engineering =====\n* Soil Mechanics Lab\n* Strength of Materials Lab\n* Fluid Lab\n* Environment Lab\n* Public Health Lab\n* Transportation Lab\n* Concrete Lab\n\n===== Department of Urban & Regional Planning =====\n* GIS Laboratory\n* Cartography Laboratory<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/articles/Laboratories/211|title=Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology - RUET|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2016-12-03}}</ref>\n\n==== ''Faculty of Mechanical Engineering'' ====\n\n===== Department of Mechanical Engineering =====\n* Thermal Engineering Lab (Heat Engine Lab)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/articles/List%20of%20Laboratories/93|title=Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology - RUET|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2016-12-03}}</ref>\n* Fluid Mechanics and Energy Lab\n* Applied Mechanics and Machine Design Lab\n* Material Science and Metallurgy Lab\n* Metrology Lab\n* Wood Shop\n* Machine Shop\n* Foundry Shop\n* Boiler Shop\n* Fitting Shop\n* Welding & Sheet Metal Shop\n* Computer Lab\n\n===== Department of Glass and Ceramic Engineering =====\n* Ceramic Forming Lab\n* Micro-structure Lab\n* Ceramic Testing Lab<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/articles/Laboratories/142|title=Department of Glass and Ceramic Engineering Laboratories, RUET|last=|first=|date=|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|publisher=|access-date=2016-12-03}}</ref>\n\n==== ''Faculty Of Electrical and Computer Engineering'' ====\n\n===== Department of Electrical and Electronic Engineering =====\n* Electrical Machine LAB<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/articles/Laboratories/158|title=Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology - RUET|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2016-12-03}}</ref>\n* Electronics and Power Electronics Lab\n* Electrical Circuit and Measurement Lab\n* Computer Lab(1)\n* Telecommunications and Microwave Lab\n* Photovoltaic and Nanotechnology Lab\n*Computer Lab(2)\n*Power Electronics & Green Energy lab.\n* High Voltage Lab\n\n===== Department of Computer Science and Engineering =====\n* Software Lab<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/articles/Laboratories%20in%20Dept.%20of%20CSE/78|title=Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology - RUET|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2016-12-03}}</ref>\n* Network Lab\n* Operating System Lab\n* Hardware Lab\n* ACL Lab\n* Game and Android Development Lab\n\n===== Department of Electronics and Telecommunication Engineering =====\n* Communication Laboratory<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/articles/Laboratories/195|title=Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology - RUET|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2016-12-03}}</ref>\n* Antenna and Propagation Laboratory\n* Photonics Laboratory\n* Digital Signal Processing Laboratory\n* Microelectronics Laboratory\n\n==== Other laboratories ====\n* Physics Lab<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/articles/Laboratories/154|title=Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology - RUET|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2016-12-03}}</ref>\n* Chemistry Lab\n\n=== Further development ===\nIn February, 2017, [[Bangladesh Planning Commission#Executive Committee of the National Economic Council .28ECNEC.29|Executive Committee of National Economic Council (ECNEC)]] has approved 3.40 billion Taka to implement a mega project for the RUET, aiming to well decorate and development the whole campus and its education and research. The ECNEC approved the project in the name of \"Further Development Project of RUET\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thefinancialexpress-bd.com/2017/02/15/61948/Tk-3.40m-mega-project-for-RUET-development|title=Tk 3.40m mega-project for RUET development|newspaper=The Financial Express|access-date=2 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Student life==\n\n=== Accommodation ===\nStudent dormitories (called halls) are important features in campus life. There are seven residential halls. One of them, namely Deshratna Sheikh Hasina Hall, is for female students and the remaining ones are for male students. The administrative head of a hall is its provost, usually chosen from the more senior teachers. The halls are mostly named after national heroes and leaders. These are listed below with their capacities:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/articles/Accommodation/19|title=Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology - RUET|website=www.ruet.ac.bd|access-date=2016-12-03}}</ref> \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name of the halls\n! Capacity\n|-\n|Shahid Shahidul Islam Hall\n|225\n|-\n|Shahid Abdul Hamid Hall\n|225\n|-\n|Tin Shed Hall (extension of Shahid Sahidul Islam Hall)\n|100\n|-\n|Deshratna Sheikh Hasina Hall\n|120\n|-\n|Shahid President Ziaur Rahman Hall\n|500\n|-\n|Bangabondhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman Hall\n|250\n|-\n|Shahid Lieutenant Salim hall\n|350\n|}\n\n===Organisations and clubs===\nStudents of RUET are involved in different organisations and clubs of the university. Members of these organisations and clubs organise different national programs at RUET.<ref>{{cite news |title=Campus corner |url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/printversion/details/41281 |newspaper=The Independent |location=Dhaka |date=2016-04-21 |access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref> They also participate in different national and international competitions and shows indomitable performances.<ref>{{cite news |title=RUET clinches championship in eco-run-2015 contest |url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/printversion/details/27475 |newspaper=The Independent |location=Dhaka |agency=BSS |date=2015-12-21 |access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref> Some of the leading organisations and clubs of RUET are mentioned here. \n* IEEE RUET Student Branch\n* Robotic Society of RUET (RSR)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rsr-ruet.org/|title=www.rsr-ruet.org {{!}} Robotic Society of RUET|website=www.rsr-ruet.org|access-date=2016-12-06}}</ref>\n* Society of Automotive Engineers-RUET (SAER)\n* Civil Engineering Society of RUET<ref>{{cite news |title=Campus corner |url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/printversion/details/32316 |newspaper=The Independent |location=Dhaka |date=2016-02-01 |access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref>\n* RUET Debating Club (RUET DC)\n* RUET Career Forum (RCF)<ref>{{cite news |title=Two-day job fair starts at Ruet |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/city/two-day-job-fair-starts-ruet-199129 |newspaper=The Daily Star |date=2016-01-09 |access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref>\n* Telecommunication Club\n* RUET Analytical Programming Lab (RAPL)\n* Astronomy and Science Society of RUET ( ASSR )\n* \u0985\u09a8\u09c1\u09b0\u09a3\u09a8: The cultural Club of RUET\n* \u09b8\u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09c1\u09aa\u09be\u09a4\u09bf\u0995 : A voluntary organisation of RUET\n* Photographic Society of RUET (PSR) (Zinnur Rahman is the media secretary of PSR Committee since 2019-2020)\n* RUET Cricket Club\n* RUET Football Club (RUET FC)\n* Society of Computer Aided Designer, RUET (SCADR)\n* RUET Earthquake Society\n* RUET AutoCad Club\n* Tennis Club RUET \n* Team Crack Platoon\n* RUET Fitness Club\n* \u09a8\u09bf\u09b0\u09be\u09aa\u09a6 \u09b0\u0995\u09cd\u09a4\u09c7\u09b0 \u09ac\u09a8\u09cd\u09a7\u09a8(\u09a8\u09bf\u09b0\u09ac) : A voluntary blood donating organisation of RUET\n* Machine Learning Group Of RUET\n* RUET English Language Club (RELC)\n* RUET Firefox Club\n* Cube Club of RUET\n* RUET Film Club\n* Mathematical Society of RUET\n* RUET Tourist Club\n* RUET HAWKS (RUET Basketball Club)\n* RUET Chess Club\n* Innovation Society of RUET (ISR)\n\n=== Others ===\nThe athletic club of the university provides multi-purpose sports facilities to the students to acquire physical fitness indispensable for a healthy mind and body. The university maintains a beautiful playground for football, cricket, badminton, volleyball, long tennis, basketball, etc. Indoor facilities are also available in the physical education building close to the playground.\n\nRUET has a library, a central computer center, an auditorium, a canteen, a cafeteria, a medical center, a postal service and a banking service. RUET also has its own regular bus service almost everywhere in the Rajshahi city for the convenience of student transportation. Students these are residing in the city outside the campus can take this transport service to reached the campus due time.\n\n==Awards==\n* RUET won the IEEE Photonics GSF Award, USA in October 2009\n* RUET won the Marubun Research Promotion Award, Japan in March 2009\n\n==Education cost==\nYearly academic cost is $40 (2800 Taka) (approx) in all departments. Admission cost is $213 (18,000Taka) (approx) including academic cost (admission, session, registration and student fees), medical costs, library, sports, convocation (3500 Taka) and others expenditure and for one time in four years bachelor's degree.<ref name=\"ksdroy\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ruet.ac.bd/articles/Study%20Expenditure/228 |title=RUET Study Expenditure |website=RUET  |accessdate=2015-01-24}}</ref>\n\n== Photos ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Shahid Zia Hall.jpg|Shahid Zia Hall\nFile:Bongobondhu Hall Ruet.jpg|Bangabandhu Hall\nFile:Ladies Hall.jpg|Ladies Hall\n</gallery>\n{{commons category|Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Universities in Bangladesh]]\n* [[Bangladesh University of Engineering and Technology|BUET]]\n* [[Chittagong University of Engineering & Technology|CUET]]\n* [[Khulna University of Engineering & Technology|KUET]]\n* [[University Grants Commission (Bangladesh)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n01.[http://m.banglatribune.com/national/news/348953/%E0%A6%B0%E0%A7%81%E0%A7%9F%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%9F%E0%A7%87-%E0%A6%A8%E0%A6%A4%E0%A7%81%E0%A6%A8-%E0%A6%AD%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%B8%E0%A6%BF-%E0%A6%A1.-%E0%A6%AE%E0%A7%8B.-%E0%A6%B0%E0%A6%AB%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%95%E0%A7%81%E0%A6%B2-%E0%A6%87%E0%A6%B8%E0%A6%B2%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%AE-%E0%A6%B6%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%96  \u09b0\u09c1\u09af\u09bc\u09c7\u099f\u09c7\u09b0 \u09a8\u09a4\u09c1\u09a8 \u09ad\u09bf\u09b8\u09bf \u09a1. \u09ae\u09cb. \u09b0\u09ab\u09bf\u0995\u09c1\u09b2 \u0987\u09b8\u09b2\u09be\u09ae \u09b6\u09c7\u0996 ]\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Rajshahi University of Engineering & Technology}}\n* [http://www.ruet.ac.bd Official website of RUET]\n* [http://www.rsr-ruet.org Website of Robotic Society of RUET]\n* [http://www.ipetalks.com Website of IPE Department]\n\n{{Public Universities of Bangladesh}}\n{{Public Engineering Universities of Bangladesh}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rajshahi University Of Engineering and Technology}}\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1964]]\n[[Category:1964 establishments in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Technological institutes of Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Public engineering universities of Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Engineering universities and colleges in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Education in Rajshahi]]\n", "name_user": "Engr. Md. Nadimul Islam", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_